{"title_page": "Kazuma Kiryu", "text_new": "{{Expand Japanese|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color       = #AC2121\n| name        = Kazuma Kiryu\n| series      = [[Yakuza (series)|Yakuza]]\n| image       = Kazuma Kiryu in Yakuza 6.jpg\n| caption     = Kazuma Kiryu as he appears in ''[[Yakuza 6: The Song of Life]]'' (2016)\n| first       = ''[[Yakuza (video game)|Yakuza]]'' (2005)\n| last        = ''[[Yakuza: Like a Dragon]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|last=Cryer|first=Hirun|title=It Looks Like Kiryu Kazuma is Back for Yakuza 7|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/kiryu-kazuma-appears-to-return-for-yakuza-7|website=USGamer|date=13 Nov 2019|accessdate=21 Nov 2019}}</ref>\n| portrayer   = {{Unbulleted list|[[Masakatsu Funaki]] (''Like a Dragon: Prologue'')|[[Kazuki Kitamura]] (''Like a Dragon'')}}\n| voice       = {{Unbulleted list|'''Japanese'''|[[Takaya Kuroda]]<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web |title=Kazuma Kiryu Voice - Yakuza franchise |url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Yakuza/Kazuma-Kiryu/ |website=Behind The Voice Actors |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>|'''English'''|[[Darryl Kurylo]] (''Yakuza'')<ref name=\"btva\"/>}}\n| alias       = Dragon of Dojima\n| affiliation = Tojo Clan\n| nationality = Japanese\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Kazuma Kiryu'''|\u6850\u751f \u4e00\u99ac|Kiry\u016b Kazuma|lead=yes}} is a fictional character and the [[main protagonist]] in Sega's [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[Japanese role-playing game]] series ''[[Yakuza (series)|Yakuza]]''. Kiryu is a [[yakuza]] who takes the blame for his boss' death to protect his best friend, resulting in his expulsion from the clan and a ten-year stay in prison. After leaving prison, Kiryu realizes the crime world has changed and fights against the new threats in his life. He is voiced by [[Takaya Kuroda]] in Japanese and by [[Darryl Kurylo]] in the English version of the first game.\n\nKiryu was created to appeal to a broad audience, and was the series' playable character during its first three games. Critical reception to Kiryu has been generally positive, and he is often considered a [[PlayStation]] mascot.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallagher|first1=Simon|title=10 Characters We Want To See In Playstation All-Stars Battle Royale|url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/10-characters-we-want-to-see-in-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale|website=What Culture|accessdate=30 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730151201/http://whatculture.com/gaming/10-characters-we-want-to-see-in-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale|archivedate=30 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ramsey|first1=Robert|title=Feature: 5 Reasons Why Kazuma Kiryu Is the Hardest Man on PlayStation|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2017/01/feature_5_reasons_why_kazuma_kiryu_is_the_hardest_man_on_playstation|website=Pushsquare|publisher=Gamernetwork|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref> Several have praised how Kiryu, despite identifying as a yakuza, stood out because of his kindness and [[character arc|character development]] across the series' story. On the other hand, he has also been viewed as a somewhat typical gaming protagonist.\n\n==Creation and development==\n[[File:Toshihiro Nagoshi 20140125.jpg|thumb|left|Writer Toshihiro Nagoshi created Kazuma Kiryu with Hasei Seishu's aid in the making of the series.]]\nIn creating Kazuma Kiryu, there were some issues regarding how realistic his position and age were. Writer Hasei Seishu told the staff the positions were too high for his age and thus Kiryu's age was revised. When describing Kiryu, the staff found his position would be of the noble samurai type who would often protect others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3153161|title=A Heart-To-Heart With Yakuza's Development Team|website=1UP.com|date=October 9, 2008|author=Gifford, Kevin|accessdate=March 28, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701161732/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3153161|archivedate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> According to Sega producer [[Toshihiro Nagoshi]], dragons have a strong image about them, and that when players sample it, they would, as the title suggests, get a feel for the strength and manliness of the main character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/11/ryu-ga-gotoku-update|title=Ryu Ga Gotoku Update|date=September 11, 2005|accessdate=May 10, 2014|website=IGN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512222226/http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/11/ryu-ga-gotoku-update|archivedate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> When the spin-off ''Yakuza Kenzan'' was released, he commented that the tale of Kazuma Kiryu had yet to be completed. As a result, he had Kiryu and Haruka trying to live a \"more 'human' life\" throughout ''Yakuza 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/toshihiro-nagoshi-discusses-yakuza-3|title=Toshihiro Nagoshi Discusses Yakuza 3|website=1UP.com|date=October 9, 2008|author=Gifford, Kevin|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329141335/http://www.1up.com/news/toshihiro-nagoshi-discusses-yakuza-3|archivedate=March 29, 2014}}</ref> For this game Toshihiro Nagoshi stated Kiryu was highly different from an iconic hero as a result of the way he enjoys his life. Furthermore, Nagoshi said this difference is shown across the series. Nagoshi thanked staff member Yokoyama that the team could further develop Kiryu's appeal across the franchise. The inclusion of Kiryu running an orphanage for ''Yakuza 3'' was enjoyed by Yokoyama despite rewriting this subplot multiple times. Originally, Kiryu was meant to go to prison once again but because it was going to be obvious they changed his story in this game. Due to Kiryu taking care of the orphans, Yokoyama feared the character became too kind.<ref name=\"kuroda\">{{cite book|title=Ryu ga Gotoku 3 Guidebook|pages=522\u2013527}}</ref>\n\nAcross all these games, the development team developed a sturdy understanding of his personality, and there was a lot of effort put into making the character attractive to the audiences as a result of being the only playable character. By ''Yakuza 4'', Kiryu was seen as \"indestructible\" by the staff, and as a result, he was made the last character playable in the game, following three new characters that stood out thanks to their different traits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/35429/Interview_Defining_Direction_Writing_Art_And_Music_On_Yakuza_4.php|title=Interview: Defining Direction, Writing, Art And Music On Yakuza 4|website=Gamasutra|date=June 28, 2011|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329100644/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/35429/Interview_Defining_Direction_Writing_Art_And_Music_On_Yakuza_4.php|archivedate=March 29, 2014}}</ref> In localizing the games, the character was often referred to by his first name, but by ''Yakuza 4'', producer Yasuhiro Noguchi made him most commonly called Kiryu in an attempt to make him fit with the other main characters also called by their last names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/04/13/yakuza-4-producer-yasuhiro-noguchi-on-re-localizing-the-series/|title=Yakuza 4 producer Yasuhiro Noguchi on re-localizing the series|publisher=Joystiq|date=June 28, 2011|accessdate=April 8, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408231529/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/04/13/yakuza-4-producer-yasuhiro-noguchi-on-re-localizing-the-series/|archivedate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> For ''Yakuza 5'', while once again there were other protagonists alongside Kiryu, a new one, Haruka, was added as playable for the first time in order to make her character arc connect with the role of Kiryu and the other characters. Kiryu was made into a taxi driver but in a new city where he is not known by other people by the staff as they thought it would be the best choice for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2015/06/yakuza-5-welcome-world-yakuza-5-developer-interview-part-one|title=Yakuza 5 Welcome to the World of Yakuza 5 developer interview, part one|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the prequel ''Yakuza 0'' Sega wanted to make Majima stand out from the Kiryu as in this title the two share the role of protagonists. Sega described Kiryu as a \"straight man trait \u2013 tough but honorable and keeps to himself a bit\" implying there are not too many difficulties in writing him. Through this game and the remake of the first game, ''Kiwami'', the relationship between Kiryu and Majima becomes more explored in contrast to the initial game of the franchise, most notably because of the changes made to Majima's characterization and the way he sees Kiryu's actions while being both friends and enemies at the same time. ''Yakuza 0'' also served as a story of Kiryu that Sega wanted players to know before reaching ''Yakuza 6''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/02/21/sega-on-the-challenges-of-bringing-yakuza-0-west.aspx|title=How Sega Brought Yakuza 0 To The West|date=February 21, 2017|magazine=Game Informer|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Gwaltney, Javy}}</ref> Kiryu's traits in ''Yakuza 0'' were specifically changed to a \"loose-cannon hot-head\" to the point long time fans would be surprised by his actions. However, chief Masayoshi Yokoyama stated the character would mature across the storyline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/the-yakuza-prequel-was-a-long-time-coming-1627835600|title=The Yakuza Prequel Was a Long Time Coming|date=August 28, 2014|website=Kotaku|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Nakamura, Toshi}}</ref> Despite Kiryu's fame, Sato noted that players ended up enjoying Majima far more in the franchise.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/e3-2018/2018/06/13/yakuzas-producer-discusses-possibility-of-a-majima-spin-off|title=Yakuza's Producer Discusses Possibility Of A Majima Spin-Off|magazine=Game Informer|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring development of ''Yakuza 4'', the staff started wondering how would they end Kiryu's story as, unlike other video game characters, he did not possess supernatural powers. They compared the character with [[James Bond]] whose actor changed multiple times across his movies. Describing him as \"a super-cool and masculine guy, but since he's a well-established character with a specific personality, there are things that he would and wouldn't do\" the team decided he would need a successor who would bring the staff more creativity to work with.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/yakuza-creator-talks-007-inspirations-wacky-humor-/1100-6451146/|title=Yakuza Creator Talks 007 Inspirations, Wacky Humor, And What's Next|website=GameSpot|accessdate=October 28, 2017|date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> In late 2016, Nagoshi claimed he had been doing Kazuma's story for nearly a decade, stating \"it had its pros and cons\". He concluded saying \"I also think that's a way to give back to Kazuma Kiryu. Sooner or later, I want to announce something different.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2016/12/4gamer-interviews-japanese-creators-2017-ambitions|title=4Gamer interviews Japanese creators on 2017 ambitions|publisher=Gematsu|date=December 27, 2016|accessdate=December 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228022701/http://gematsu.com/2016/12/4gamer-interviews-japanese-creators-2017-ambitions|archivedate=December 28, 2016}}</ref> In April 2017 Sega confirmed that while ''Yakuza 6'' will end Kiryu's story, the series will still go on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/170178-Yakuza-Game-in-The-Works|title=A New Yakuza Game is in The Works|publisher=Escapist|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017|author=Bogos, Steven}}</ref> Deciding to bring the last tale Kiryu with ''Yakuza 6'', the staff wanted to do the game as appealing as possible.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Famitsu|date=July 28, 2016|language=Japanese|transcript=http://yakuzafan.com/nagoshi-san-famitsu-interview/}}</ref> The game focuses on the family relationship between Kiryu and Haruka after years of being separated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2017/11/yakuza-6-song-life-previously-yakuza-trailer-launch-edition-box-art|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life \u2018Previously on Yakuza\u2026\u2019 trailer, launch edition box art|publisher=Gematsu|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Voice actors===\nEnglish voice actor [[Darryl Kurylo]] said that he wanted to sound as good as possible after being impressed by the characterization of Kiryu and the lines he had to give. However, he regrets some lines were lost in translation of the original game. Nevertheless, Kurylo enjoyed the experience to the point of playing the game multiple times alongside his son. In order to fit the lipsyncing from the original Japanese game, Kurylo often had to say a line in different styles. Kurylo still found more fun when doing the yells for the fight scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tojohq.github.io/interview-darryl-kurylo/|title=TojoHQ Interviews - Darryl Kurylo|publisher=TojoHQ|accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNogashi was impressed by Kiryu's Japanese voice actor, [[Takaya Kuroda]], due to how he sang in the music minigame. Another staff member, Sato, was impressed by the karaoke game as it helped to show a fun side of Kiryu.<ref name=\"kuroda\">{{cite book|title=Ryu ga Gotoku 3 Guidebook|pages=522\u2013527}}</ref> Kuroda highly enjoyed voicing his character, being anxious in most scenes regardless of the tone he had to make. As a result, he wants to keep Kiryu in character. Kuroda describes Kiryu as a true shy character, stating he does not consider himself too attractive to the point he could not form a formal romantic relationship with Sayama in ''Yakuza 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsbeezer.com/franceeng/interview-with-daisuke-sato-and-takaya-kuroda/|title=TojoHQ Interviews - Darryl Kurylo|publisher=News Beezer|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n{{expand section|date=October 2017}}\n\n===''Yakuza''===\n{{main article|Yakuza (video game)|Yakuza Kiwami}}\nKiryu is a famous member of the Tojo clan, who earned the nickname of {{Nihongo|\"the Dragon of Dojima\"|\u5802\u5cf6\u306e\u9f8d|D\u014djima no Ry\u016b}}. Early in the first game he was planning on starting his own subsidiary group until he takes the blame for the murder of his boss, Sohei Dojima, to protect his best friend, Akira Nishikiyama, and is imprisoned for ten years.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Yakuza 2|publisher=Sega|quote=Kiryu: I was sentenced to ten years. After going inside I got a letter of expulsion from the Dojima Family and found out Yumi had disappeared.|developer=Sega}}</ref> After his release, Kiryu returns to his home town, Kamurocho, but due to his patricide he is marked for death by the entire [[yakuza]] community. Kiryu then learns that 10 billion yen has been stolen from the Tojo Clan. Soon after he meets a young girl called Haruka, whom seemingly every criminal group in the country is after. With help of detective Date, Kiryu manages to learn the truth of the money. Upon reuniting with Yumi, his childhood love and Haruka's mother he is confronted by Kyohei Jingu, Haruka's father, and the true owner of the money. After defeating Jingu, Kiryu is reunited with his old friend Nishiki. The two fight, with Kiryu coming out victorious. Jingu tries to shoot Kiryu but Yumi takes the bullet for him. Nishikiyama then kills himself with Jingu. After Yumi dies in Kiryu's arms, Kiryu subsequently decides to start a new, honest life with Haruka.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Yakuza 2|publisher=Sega|quote=Date: Snap out of it! You've still got something to fight for! There's someone who needs you! Don't run from your responsibilities!|developer=Sega}}</ref>\n\n===''Yakuza 2''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 2|Yakuza Kiwami 2}}\nIn ''[[Yakuza 2]]'', the fifth Chairman of the Tojo Clan, Yukio Terada, is assassinated and Kazuma Kiryu wants Sohei Dojima's son Daigo to take the clan's leadership and prevent an upcoming yakuza families war. While attempting to broker a peace deal between the Tojo and the Omi, Daigo and Jin Goda, Omi chairman, are kidnapped by Ryuji Goda, Jin's adopted son. Ryuji, through working with the Jingweon mafia, attempts to destroy Kamurocho and Kiryu to be the only dragon in Japan. Kiryu is put under the protective custody of a female detective called Kaoru Sayama, who uses him to get close to the Tojo to discover her past. Eventually, Kiryu and Ryuji fight atop Kamurocho Hills. Kiryu is victorious, but Yukio Terada appears, revealing that he faked his own death to start a war and is really a Jingweon survivor. Terada is also defeated, but begs Kiryu to trust him. After Jin Goda, Takashima and Terada are dead, Kiryu and Ryuji have a final showdown, which Kiryu wins. A bomb Terada had triggered, but secretly removed the fuse from, fails to detonate, saving Kiryu and Kaoru's lives.\n\n===''Yakuza 3''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 3}}\nFor ''[[Yakuza 3]]'' Kiryu leaves Kamurocho for [[Okinawa]], where he now runs the Morning Glory Orphanage. There he raises nine children, including Haruka Sawamura. He is caught up in a government plot when Morning Glory's land is in the way of a proposed resort.\n\n===''Yakuza 4''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 4}}\nDuring ''[[Yakuza 4]]'', Kiryu continues to run the orphanage. However, he is once again involved in the matters back in Kamurocho, having found Saejima washed ashore one day. Saejima tells him a man called Hamazaki told him to find Kiryu. Some time after Saejima leaves, Hamazaki washes ashore. After meeting up with Yasuko, Hamazaki sends the two on ahead to Kamurocho. There Kiryu leaves Yasuko at New Serena, but returns to find her missing after witness [[Goro Majima]] being arrested and dragged away from Millennium Tower to police patrol cars. He chases her into the sewers, where Tanimura and Akiyama mistake him for an Ueno Seiwa Clan member, and attack. After defeating them Kiryu chases Yasuko to the roof, where he finds her and Saejima bound and gagged by Katsuragi. During the events that follow Yasuko is shot and kills Katsuragi before dying herself. Kiryu later fights Daigo on top of the Millennium Tower.\n\n===''Yakuza 5''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 5}}\nIn ''[[Yakuza 5]]'', Kiryu has left the orphanage in Okinawa and becomes a taxi driver in Fukuoka under a false identity.\n\n===''Yakuza 6: The Song of Life''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 6: The Song of Life}}\nIn ''[[Yakuza 6: The Song of Life]]'', ex-idol and daughter figure to series protagonist Kazuma Kiryu, Haruka Sawamura, is involved in a mysterious hit-and-run. Finding out who is responsible takes Kiryu reluctantly back into the extra-judicial underbelly of Japan \u2014 Kamurocho, as well as a small fishing town near Hiroshima called Onomichi. Yakuza 6 is the final chapter in Kiryu's saga and closes out his story.\n\n===''Yakuza 0''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 0}}\nSeventeen years prior to the events of the first game, Kiryu is framed for killing a civilian during a routine debt collection and must find the true killer before his family is forced to take responsibility on his behalf. While he attempts to uncover the mysteries behind the murder, he becomes entangled in a ruthless real estate war.\n\n===''Yakuza: Like a Dragon''===\nWhile not its main protagonist, Kiryu is scheduled to appear in the upcoming ''[[Yakuza: Like a Dragon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cryer|first=Hirun|title=It Looks Like Kiryu Kazuma is Back for Yakuza 7|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/kiryu-kazuma-appears-to-return-for-yakuza-7|website=USGamer|date=November 13, 2019|accessdate=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spinoffs and other appearances===\n[[File:Masakatsu Funaki.jpg|thumb|Masakatsu Funaki portrays Kiryu in the first film of the series.]]\nDuring the events of the zombie spinoff ''[[Yakuza: Dead Souls]]'', he returns to Kamurocho after Haruka is kidnapped by a mysterious man. In the film adaptation ''[[Like a Dragon: Prologue]]'', he is portrayed by [[Masakatsu Funaki]]. This film serves as a prequel of the first ''Yakuza'' game describing Kiryu's youth where he meets recurring characters from the series. As he grows up, Kiryu starts desiring to form his own group, but gives up on this when his girlfriend is sexually assaulted and he decides to take the blame for killing the person to protect Nishikiyama. In the film, ''[[Like a Dragon]]'', an adaptation of the first ''Yakuza'' game, he is portrayed by  [[Kazuki Kitamura]]. In the ''Yakuza'' stage show, he is portrayed by Eiji Takigawa.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-04-13/yakuza-stage-play-leads-photographed-in-costume/.87090|title=Yakuza Stage Play's Leads Photographed in Costume|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=April 13, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414044009/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-04-13/yakuza-stage-play-leads-photographed-in-costume/.87090|archivedate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOutside the ''Yakuza'' series, Kiryu appears as a guest character in ''[[Binary Domain]]'' through an unlockable code and ''[[Everybody's Golf 6]]'' through downloadable content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-stealths-binary-domain/|title=Yakuza's Kazuma Kiryu stealths into Binary Domain|publisher=GamesRadar|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515153936/http://www.gamesradar.com/yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-stealths-binary-domain/|archivedate=May 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2013/04/kazuma-kiryu-coming-to-hot-shots-golf-world-invitational|title=Kazuma Kiryu coming to Hot Shots Golf: World Invitational|publisher=Gematsu|date=April 17, 2013|accessdate=July 30, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816124950/http://gematsu.com/2013/04/kazuma-kiryu-coming-to-hot-shots-golf-world-invitational|archivedate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> He is also a playable in ''[[Project X Zone 2]]'' alongside Majima.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2015/04/12/project-x-zone-2-coming-west-fall/ |title=Project X Zone 2 Is Coming To The West This Fall |publisher=Siliconera |accessdate=April 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150414205701/http://www.siliconera.com/2015/04/12/project-x-zone-2-coming-west-fall/ |archivedate=April 14, 2015 }}</ref> In ''[[Fist of the North Star: Lost Paradise]]'', a ''Yakuza'' spinoff based on ''[[Fist of the North Star]]'', Kiryu appears as a [[skin (video gaming)|skin]] for [[Kenshiro]] via downloadable content.<ref>https://www.destructoid.com/fist-of-the-north-star-s-kiryu-dlc-will-be-free-for-two-weeks-522567.phtml</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical===\nCritical reception to Kiryu's character has been generally positive. Juan Castro from [[IGN]] praised him as an appealing character noting, both his violent traits as well as his kindness. They further noted that while being a \"badass\", he stands out thanks to his kindness.<ref name=\"ignreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/06/yakuza-review|title=Yakuza review|date=September 6, 2006|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226222214/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/06/yakuza-review|archivedate=February 26, 2014}}</ref> The same website listed him as a notorious anti-hero as he \"walks a fine line between good and bad.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/03/05/gamings-most-notorious-anti-heroes?page=4|title=GAMING'S MOST NOTORIOUS ANTI-HEROES|website=IGN|accessdate=May 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317012423/http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/03/05/gamings-most-notorious-anti-heroes?page=4|archivedate=March 17, 2014}}</ref> Cheat Code Central expressed similar comments noting that despite the character's occupation, he is so kind he takes the blame of Dojima's death in the start of the first game resulting in the expulsion from his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatcc.com/psx2/rev/yakuzareview.html#ixzz2xFtxSCWe|title=Yakuza review|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328211911/http://www.cheatcc.com/psx2/rev/yakuzareview.html#ixzz2xFtxSCWe|archivedate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> [[Eurogamer]] similarly commented that \"Despite all the violence, Kazuma is quite a personable bloke, whose love for his friends sees him banged up for ten years over a murder his 'brother' Nishiki committed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_yakuza_ps2|title=Yakuza review|website=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226163827/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_yakuza_ps2|archivedate=February 26, 2014}}</ref> VideoGamer.com's Wesley Yin-Poole also shared similar commenting adding that \" Kazuma isn't averse to the odd spot of humanitarian work either - he's just a big softy really.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps2/yakuza/review.html|title=Yakuza Review|publisher=VideoGamer.com|date=September 28, 2006|author=Yin-Poole, Wesley|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328204610/http://www.videogamer.com/ps2/yakuza/review.html|archivedate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> Greg Orlando from the magazine ''[[Newtype]]'' found him entertaining due to multiple actions he does across the series.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Orlando |first=Greg |url=http://www.newtype-usa.com/reviews/index.php?itemid=315 |title=Yakuza |work=Newtype USA |volume=5 |issue=9 |date=September 2006 |issn=1541-4817 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061124041801/http://www.newtype-usa.com/reviews/index.php?itemid=315 |archivedate=November 24, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When reviewing ''Yakuza 3'', Sam Marchello from RPGamer noted the character's notable development comparing his life with the Yakuza to the orphans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/yakuza/yakuza3/reviews/yakuza3strev1.html|title=Yakuza 3 - Staff Review|publisher=RPGamer.com|author=Marchello, Sam|accessdate=March 29, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004901/http://www.rpgamer.com/games/yakuza/yakuza3/reviews/yakuza3strev1.html|archivedate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> Greg Miller from IGN noted how developers wanted players to connect to Kiryu's side in ''Yakuza 3'' as a result of being his motivation, resulting in several cutscenes and minigames which left him mixed feelings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/09/yakuza-3-review?page=2|title=Yakuza 3 Review|website=IGN|author=Miller, Greg|accessdate=March 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330054709/http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/09/yakuza-3-review?page=2|archivedate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> Anthony John Agnello from [[GamesRadar]] praised Kiryu's initial appearance alongside his personality.<ref>{{cite web|title=Why I Love: Kazuma Kiryu's suit in Yakuza|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/why-i-love-kazuma-kiryus-suit-yakuza/|accessdate=April 16, 2016|author=Agnello, Anthony John|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|date=December 18, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924164945/http://www.gamesradar.com/why-i-love-kazuma-kiryus-suit-yakuza/|archivedate=September 24, 2016}}</ref> Matt Kim from US Gamer said Kiryu was his favorite paternal figure in gaming due to how caring he is to Haruka and to people in general despite his connections with the yakuza.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/community-question-whos-your-favorite-dad-in-video-games|title=Who's Your Favorite Dad in Video Games?|publisher=US Gamer|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Push Square listed him as one of the best characters seen in PlayStation games based on his skills in combat and sense of justice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2017/01/feature_5_reasons_why_kazuma_kiryu_is_the_hardest_man_on_playstation|title=Feature: 5 Reasons Why Kazuma Kiryu Is the Hardest Man on PlayStation|publisher=Push Square|accessdate=June 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn a more critical view, [[Greg Kasavin]] from [[GameSpot]] stated that while Kiryu often resorts to profanity \"he's your prototypical hero taking on your prototypical villains.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yakuza review|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-review/1900-6157009/|accessdate=March 28, 2014|website=GameSpot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208032949/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-review/1900-6157009/|archivedate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> [[1UP.com]] called him \"a hard-boiled thug\" comparing him with characters like [[Niko Bellic|Niko]] and [[Alex Mercer (Prototype)|Alex Mercer]] due to his inhuman powers. They further noted that his powers can be \"ridiculous.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberty for All: How We Arrived at GTA4, Infamous, and Prototype|url=http://www.1up.com/features/liberty-arrived-gta4-infamous-prototype?pager.offset=2|accessdate=October 7, 2015|website=1UP.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608165721/http://www.1up.com/features/liberty-arrived-gta4-infamous-prototype?pager.offset=2|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Real life yakuza Midoriyama commented on the character during a review of the third game that \"Kiryu is the way yakuza used to be. We kept the streets clean. People liked us. We didn't bother ordinary citizens. We respected our bosses. Now, guys like that only exist in video games.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yakuza 3 reviewed by Yakuza|url=http://boingboing.net/2010/08/10/yakuza-3-review.html|accessdate=March 28, 2014|publisher=BoingBoing|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208192152/http://boingboing.net/2010/08/10/yakuza-3-review.html|archivedate=February 8, 2014}}</ref> In a ''[[Famitsu]]'' poll from 2010, Kiryu was voted as the eleventh best video game character.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Snake Beats Mario, Is Coolest Video Game Character Ever\n |url         = http://www.1up.com/news/snake-beats-mario-coolest-video\n |date        = February 10, 2010\n |accessdate  = October 7, 2015\n |website   = 1UP.com\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6i8KLI3kn?url=http://www.1up.com/news/snake-beats-mario-coolest-video\n |archivedate = 2016-06-09\n}}</ref> In a retrospective of the series, GameSpot compared Kiryu with [[Michael Corleone]], the protagonist of the novel ''[[The Godfather (novel)|The Godfather]]'' by [[Mario Puzo]]. GameSpot noted that while Kiryu was featured with pacifistic traits as he wishes to have a peaceful life with Haruka, he still has violent traits as he has no problems with beating up enemies across the series. In addition to Kiryu's story, the site also commented on how well developed were from clunky to more unique as latter games in the franchise included new characters with different fighting styles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/amp-articles/the-history-of-yakuza/1100-6456703/|title=The History Of Yakuza|date=February 10, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2018|website=GameSpot}}</ref> \n\nCritics have also noted Kiryu was handled different in the prequel ''Yakuza 0'' and had mixed feelings on its execution. [[Anime News Network]] writer Dustin Bailey praised Kiryu's role in ''Yakuza 0'' saying that while in most of the games he was portrayed as a \"saintly [[Superman]]\", in the prequel he enjoyed seeing the character involved in darker scenarios.<ref>{{cite news|title=This Week in Games - Yakuza 0|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-x-button/2017-02-02/this-week-in-games-yakuza-0/.111745|accessdate=February 3, 2017|date=February 2, 2017|author=Bailey, Dustin|work=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202183251/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-x-button/2017-02-02/this-week-in-games-yakuza-0/.111745|archivedate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> As a result, he found the PlayStation 3 ''Yakuza'' games less interesting due to a focus on Kiryu's struggle for a peaceful life, but, conversely, found ''Yakuza 5'' to be more unique due to its inclusion of bizarre enemies for Kiryu to fight, most notably a bear.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everything You Need to Know About Yakuza|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2017-08-25/everything-you-need-to-know-about-yakuza/.119814|accessdate=August 25, 2017|date=August 25, 2017|author=Bailey, Dustin|work=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828203548/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2017-08-25/everything-you-need-to-know-about-yakuza/.119814|archivedate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> Due to Majima showing a different characterization in the prequel, writers found him as a better character than Kiryu.finding him more interesting than Kiryu.<ref name=\"des\">{{cite web |last=Glagowski |first=Peter |date=19 January 2017 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-0-412494.phtml |title=Review: Yakuza 0 |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119183035/https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-0-412494.phtml |archivedate=January 19, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"egmno\">{{cite magazine |last=Plessas |first=Nick |date=January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |title=Yakuza 0 review |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121013119/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date= January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_0/b/playstation4/archive/2017/01/19/everlasting-mob-stopper.aspx |title=Everlasting Mob Stopper - Yakuza 0 - PlayStation 4 |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120022852/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_0/b/playstation4/archive/2017/01/19/everlasting-mob-stopper.aspx |archivedate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> '[[EGMNOW]]'' liked the contrast the duo had in the narrative because of the different quests they had to pass to achieve their goals.<ref name=\"egmno\">{{cite magazine |last=Plessas |first=Nick |date=January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |title=Yakuza 0 review |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121013119/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Jimquisition]]'' said that both characters were \"like-able protagonists who consistently have to act as straight men in a variety of weird situations\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Sterling |first=Jim |date=19 January 2017 |url=http://www.thejimquisition.com/yakuza-0-review/ |title=Yakuza 0 Review \u2013 Majimagnificent |publisher=[[The Jimquisition]] |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127005102/http://www.thejimquisition.com/yakuza-0-review/ |archivedate=January 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs multiple games involved Kiryu returning to the yakuza life despite his retirement in the first game, ''USGamer'' criticized this recycling format and expected ''Yakuza 6'' follow the true end of Kiryu's arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-yakuza-series-before-yakuza-6|title=A Yakuza Primer: Everything You Need to Know About the Series Before Yakuza 6\n|accessdate=April 13, 2020|publisher=US Gamer}}</ref> For the review of ''Yakuza 6: The Song of Life'', UK Anime Network believed Sega managed to close Kiryu's story in an appealing despite his interactions with Haruto, an infant Kiryu looks after across the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/games/Yakuza_6:_The_Song_of_Life.html|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life|date=|accessdate=June 21, 2018|publisher=UK Anime Network}}</ref> Destructoid liked the handling of Kiryu, due to his more serious personality caused by Haruka's crisis.<ref name=\"Destructoid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-492903.phtml|title=Review: Yakuza 6: The Song of Life|last=Glagowski|first=Peter|website=[[Destructoid]]|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318053355/https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-492903.phtml|archivedate=18 March 2018}}</ref> GameInformer felt that the narrative gave the character an appropiate closure even if it is sad.<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_6_the_song_of_life/b/playstation4/archive/2018/03/15/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-game-informer-review.aspx|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life review|last=Cork|first=Jeff|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323223235/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_6_the_song_of_life/b/playstation4/archive/2018/03/15/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-game-informer-review.aspx|archivedate=23 March 2018}}</ref> GameRevolution shared similar comments, mainly on how Haruka also has been developing in previous games to stay close to her adoptive father and it was this time Kiryu's quest to protect her.<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/376091-yakuza-6-review-like-a-dragon|title=Yakuza 6 Review: Like a Dragon|last=Faulkner|first=Jason|publisher=[[Game Revolution]]|date=15 March 2016|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315140231/http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/376091-yakuza-6-review-like-a-dragon|archivedate=15 March 2018}}</ref> GameSpot noted the game touched deep themes as Kiryu often interacted with families, making it fitting for his final game with him as the main character.<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-review-a-hard-boiled-old/1900-6416875/|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life Review|last=Tran|first=Edmond|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=16 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318053352/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-review-a-hard-boiled-old/1900-6416875/|archivedate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Popularity===\nIn a popularity poll from 2018 by Sega, Kiryu took the 2nd position behind Goro Majima.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/09/28/yakuza-series-popularity-poll-shows-its-current-top-20-favorite-characters/|title=Yakuza Series Popularity Poll Shows Its Current Top-20 Favorite Characters|publisher=Siliconera|accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Because ''Yakuza'' has a long running history of being [[PlayStation]] exclusive, Kazuma Kiryu is often recognized as a PlayStation mascot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Playstation Mascots|url=http://watchmojo.com/suggest/Top+10+Playstation+Mascots|publisher=Watchmojo|accessdate=1 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141125131514/http://watchmojo.com/suggest/Top+10+Playstation+Mascots|archivedate=25 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=25 Characters That Need to Be in \u2018PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale\u2019|url=http://gamerant.com/playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-characters-wishlist-riley-145888/|last=Little|first=Riley|publisher=Gamerant|accessdate=1 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201011041/http://gamerant.com/playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-characters-wishlist-riley-145888/|archivedate=1 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn promoting [[Kai Razor]] and ''[[Yakuza: Dead Souls]]'', Kiryu's image was used in the razor. Kiryu also uses such razor during a scene from ''Of the End''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kai Razor Makes Yakuza's Kazuma Kiryu The Best He Can Get|url=http://andriasang.com/comu8o/yakuza_shaver/|accessdate=March 28, 2014|publisher=Andriasang|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413200226/http://andriasang.com/comu8o/yakuza_shaver/|archivedate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> Sega also sponsored a contest where the winner would get Kiryu's $9000 tattoo. The winner was Fari Salievski. The process took sixth months to complete. Salivevski commented \"Well, my nickname is now \"The Dragon\"... Whilst in Thailand, I had people coming up to me and taking photos, other cam round wondering what all the fuss was about thinking I am some kind of celebrity. I could not stop laughing! my Facebook page gets a lot of comments too.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Wins Kazuma Kiryu's $9000 Back Tattoo|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/man-wins-kazuma-kiryus-9000-back-tattoo-4783|accessdate=March 28, 2014|publisher=GameRevolution|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817205934/http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/man-wins-kazuma-kiryus-9000-back-tattoo-4783|archivedate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nKazuma Kiryu was requested as a guest character in Bandai Namco's [[fighting game]] ''[[Tekken 7]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Harada on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853769649447608320|website=Twitter|accessdate=22 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422203438/https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853769649447608320|archivedate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Harada on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853951496349663232?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http%3A%2F%2Fyakuzafan.com%2Fkazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc%2F|website=Twitter|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022150154/https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853951496349663232?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http%3A%2F%2Fyakuzafan.com%2Fkazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc%2F|archivedate=22 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Here are the top guest characters suggested to Katsuhiro Harada for Tekken 7|url=http://tekkengamer.com/2017/04/18/top-guest-characters-suggested-katsuhiro-harada-tekken-7/|website=Tekkengamer|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420235616/http://tekkengamer.com/2017/04/18/top-guest-characters-suggested-katsuhiro-harada-tekken-7/|archivedate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ross|first1=Deacon|title=Kazuma Kiryu Most Requested Character For Tekken 7 DLC!|url=http://yakuzafan.com/kazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc/|website=Yakuzafan|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420144324/http://yakuzafan.com/kazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc/|archivedate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Miche|first1=Hunter|title=Kazuma Kiryu Is The Most Requested Tekken 7 Guest Character|url=http://segmentnext.com/2017/04/22/kazuma-kiryu-requested-tekken-7-guest-character/|website=Segmentnext|accessdate=21 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422140327/http://segmentnext.com/2017/04/22/kazuma-kiryu-requested-tekken-7-guest-character/|archivedate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Passero|first1=Andrea|title=KAZUMA KIRYU COME PERSONAGGIO DI TEKKEN 7?|url=http://it.ign.com/tekken-7-ps4/124408/news/kazuma-kiryu-come-personaggio-di-tekken-7|website=IGN Italia|accessdate=22 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422143910/http://it.ign.com/tekken-7-ps4/124408/news/kazuma-kiryu-come-personaggio-di-tekken-7|archivedate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gravelle|first1=Cody|title=Yakuza Protagonist is Most Requested Guest Fighter for Tekken 7|url=https://gamerant.com/yakuza-protagonist-guest-fighter-tekken-7/|website=Gamerant|publisher=Warp 10|accessdate=23 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424001728/https://gamerant.com/yakuza-protagonist-guest-fighter-tekken-7/|archivedate=24 April 2017}}</ref> [[Katsuhiro Harada]], the producer of ''Tekken 7'' and director of the [[Tekken|series]], stated that he was taken aback by the amount of demand there was for the character in the West.<ref>{{cite web|title=There\u2019s Strong Demand For Yakuza\u2019s Kazuma Kiryu Be Included In Tekken 7|url=http://gamermalaya.my/en/theres-strong-demand-for-yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-be-in-tekken-7/|website=Gamermalaya|accessdate=2 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501143404/http://gamermalaya.my/en/theres-strong-demand-for-yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-be-in-tekken-7/|archivedate=1 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Makuch|first1=Eddie|title=Tekken 7 Boss Talks Rage-Quitting, Possible Nintendo Switch Version, Guest Characters, And More|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tekken-7-boss-talks-rage-quitting-possible-nintend/1100-6449617/|website=Gamespot|publisher=Cbs|accessdate=2 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826032131/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/tekken-7-boss-talks-rage-quitting-possible-nintend/1100-6449617/|archivedate=26 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Yakuza\u2019s Kazuma Kiryu should be in Tekken 7|url=http://segabits.com/blog/2017/05/02/why-yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-should-be-in-tekken-7/|website=Segabits|accessdate=3 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503114451/http://segabits.com/blog/2017/05/02/why-yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-should-be-in-tekken-7/|archivedate=3 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Orselli|first1=Brandon|title=TEKKEN 7 PRODUCER ASKS FANS WHAT GUEST CHARACTERS SHOULD APPEAR IN GAME|url=http://nichegamer.com/2017/04/24/tekken-7-producer-asks-fans-what-guest-characters-should-appear-in-game/|website=Nichegamer|accessdate=3 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516154038/http://nichegamer.com/2017/04/24/tekken-7-producer-asks-fans-what-guest-characters-should-appear-in-game/|archivedate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Even after the revealed guest characters were [[Geese Howard]] and [[Noctis Lucis Caelum]], fans took to Twitter to express their enthusiasm in having Kiryu included in the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Bryan|title=Forget Noctis, Here Are Other Ideas For Tekken 7 Characters|url=https://kotaku.com/forget-noctis-here-are-other-ideas-for-tekken-7-charac-1820424912|website=Kotaku|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> ''Yakuza'' producer Daisuke Sato stated that \"As far as it comes down to the whole ''Tekken'' thing, if Harada-san actually says he wants to use Kiryu, then hey.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yakuza Producer says if Harada wants Kazuma Kiryu in Tekken 7, they\u2019re for it|url=http://segabits.com/blog/2018/03/18/yakuza-producer-says-if-harada-wants-kazuma-kiryu-in-tekken-7-theyre-for-it/|website=Segabits|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rinaldi|first1=Casey|title=Yakuza series Producer Daisuke Sato says it\u2019s up to Harada if fans want to see Kazuma Kiryu in Tekken 7|url=http://shoryuken.com/2018/03/21/yakuza-series-producer-daisuke-sato-says-its-up-to-harada-if-fans-want-to-see-kazuma-kiryu-in-tekken-7/|website=Shoryuken|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=M\u00e4ki|first1=Jonas|title=Bandai Namco are free to use Kazuma Kiryu in Tekken 7|url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/news/646243/Bandai+Namco+are+free+to+use+Kazuma+Kiryu+in+Tekken+7/|website=Gamereactor|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Yakuza series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiryu, Kazuma}}\n[[Category:Action-adventure game characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional Japanese people in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional male martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional martial artists in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Fictional taxicab drivers]]\n[[Category:Fictional yakuza]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Sega protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2005]]\n[[Category:Vigilante characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Yakuza (series)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Japanese|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color       = #AC2121\n| name        = Kazuma Kiryu\n| series      = [[Yakuza (series)|Yakuza]]\n| image       = Kazuma Kiryu in Yakuza 6.jpg\n| caption     = Kazuma Kiryu as he appears in ''[[Yakuza 6: The Song of Life]]'' (2016)\n| first       = ''[[Yakuza (video game)|Yakuza]]'' (2005)\n| last        = ''[[Yakuza: Like a Dragon]]'' (2020)<ref>{{cite web|last=Cryer|first=Hirun|title=It Looks Like Kiryu Kazuma is Back for Yakuza 7|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/kiryu-kazuma-appears-to-return-for-yakuza-7|website=USGamer|date=13 Nov 2019|accessdate=21 Nov 2019}}</ref>\n| portrayer   = {{Unbulleted list|[[Masakatsu Funaki]] (''Like a Dragon: Prologue'')|[[Kazuki Kitamura]] (''Like a Dragon'')}}\n| voice       = {{Unbulleted list|'''Japanese'''|[[Takaya Kuroda]]<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web |title=Kazuma Kiryu Voice - Yakuza franchise |url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Yakuza/Kazuma-Kiryu/ |website=Behind The Voice Actors |accessdate=19 September 2019}}</ref>|'''English'''|[[Darryl Kurylo]] (''Yakuza'')<ref name=\"btva\"/>}}\n| alias       = Dragon of Dojima\n| affiliation = Tojo Clan\n| nationality = Japanese\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Kazuma Kiryu'''|\u6850\u751f \u4e00\u99ac|Kiry\u016b Kazuma|lead=yes}} is a fictional character and the [[main protagonist]] in Sega's [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[Japanese role-playing game]] series ''[[Yakuza (series)|Yakuza]]''. Kiryu is a [[yakuza]] who takes the blame for his boss' death to protect his best friend, resulting in his expulsion from the clan and a ten-year stay in prison. After leaving prison, Kiryu realizes the crime world has changed and fights against the new threats in his life. He is voiced by [[Takaya Kuroda]] in Japanese and by [[Darryl Kurylo]] in the English version of the first game.\n\nKiryu was created to appeal to a broad audience, and was the series' playable character during its first three games. Critical reception to Kiryu has been generally positive, and he is often considered a [[PlayStation]] mascot.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gallagher|first1=Simon|title=10 Characters We Want To See In Playstation All-Stars Battle Royale|url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/10-characters-we-want-to-see-in-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale|website=What Culture|accessdate=30 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160730151201/http://whatculture.com/gaming/10-characters-we-want-to-see-in-playstation-all-stars-battle-royale|archivedate=30 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ramsey|first1=Robert|title=Feature: 5 Reasons Why Kazuma Kiryu Is the Hardest Man on PlayStation|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2017/01/feature_5_reasons_why_kazuma_kiryu_is_the_hardest_man_on_playstation|website=Pushsquare|publisher=Gamernetwork|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref> Several have praised how Kiryu, despite identifying as a yakuza, stood out because of his kindness and [[character arc|character development]] across the series' story. On the other hand, he has also been viewed as a somewhat typical gaming protagonist.\n\n==Creation and development==\nIn creating Kazuma Kiryu, there were some issues regarding how realistic his position and age were. Writer Hasei Seishu told the staff the positions were too high for his age and thus Kiryu's age was revised. When describing Kiryu, the staff found his position would be of the noble samurai type who would often protect others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3153161|title=A Heart-To-Heart With Yakuza's Development Team|website=1UP.com|date=October 9, 2008|author=Gifford, Kevin|accessdate=March 28, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701161732/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=3&cId=3153161|archivedate=July 1, 2016}}</ref> According to Sega producer [[Toshihiro Nagoshi]], dragons have a strong image about them, and that when players sample it, they would, as the title suggests, get a feel for the strength and manliness of the main character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/11/ryu-ga-gotoku-update|title=Ryu Ga Gotoku Update|date=September 11, 2005|accessdate=May 10, 2014|website=IGN|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512222226/http://www.ign.com/articles/2005/09/11/ryu-ga-gotoku-update|archivedate=May 12, 2014}}</ref> When the spin-off ''Yakuza Kenzan'' was released, he commented that the tale of Kazuma Kiryu had yet to be completed. As a result, he had Kiryu and Haruka trying to live a \"more 'human' life\" throughout ''Yakuza 3''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.1up.com/news/toshihiro-nagoshi-discusses-yakuza-3|title=Toshihiro Nagoshi Discusses Yakuza 3|website=1UP.com|date=October 9, 2008|author=Gifford, Kevin|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329141335/http://www.1up.com/news/toshihiro-nagoshi-discusses-yakuza-3|archivedate=March 29, 2014}}</ref> For this game Toshihiro Nagoshi stated Kiryu was highly different from an iconic hero as a result of the way he enjoys his life. Furthermore, Nagoshi said this difference is shown across the series. Nagoshi thanked staff member Yokoyama that the team could further develop Kiryu's appeal across the franchise. The inclusion of Kiryu running an orphanage for ''Yakuza 3'' was enjoyed by Yokoyama despite rewriting this subplot multiple times. Originally, Kiryu was meant to go to prison once again but because it was going to be obvious they changed his story in this game. Due to Kiryu taking care of the orphans, Yokoyama feared the character became too kind.<ref name=\"kuroda\">{{cite book|title=Ryu ga Gotoku 3 Guidebook|pages=522\u2013527}}</ref>\n\nAcross all these games, the development team developed a sturdy understanding of his personality, and there was a lot of effort put into making the character attractive to the audiences as a result of being the only playable character. By ''Yakuza 4'', Kiryu was seen as \"indestructible\" by the staff, and as a result, he was made the last character playable in the game, following three new characters that stood out thanks to their different traits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/35429/Interview_Defining_Direction_Writing_Art_And_Music_On_Yakuza_4.php|title=Interview: Defining Direction, Writing, Art And Music On Yakuza 4|website=Gamasutra|date=June 28, 2011|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329100644/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/35429/Interview_Defining_Direction_Writing_Art_And_Music_On_Yakuza_4.php|archivedate=March 29, 2014}}</ref> In localizing the games, the character was often referred to by his first name, but by ''Yakuza 4'', producer Yasuhiro Noguchi made him most commonly called Kiryu in an attempt to make him fit with the other main characters also called by their last names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2011/04/13/yakuza-4-producer-yasuhiro-noguchi-on-re-localizing-the-series/|title=Yakuza 4 producer Yasuhiro Noguchi on re-localizing the series|publisher=Joystiq|date=June 28, 2011|accessdate=April 8, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408231529/http://www.joystiq.com/2011/04/13/yakuza-4-producer-yasuhiro-noguchi-on-re-localizing-the-series/|archivedate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> For ''Yakuza 5'', while once again there were other protagonists alongside Kiryu, a new one, Haruka, was added as playable for the first time in order to make her character arc connect with the role of Kiryu and the other characters. Kiryu was made into a taxi driver but in a new city where he is not known by other people by the staff as they thought it would be the best choice for him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2015/06/yakuza-5-welcome-world-yakuza-5-developer-interview-part-one|title=Yakuza 5 Welcome to the World of Yakuza 5 developer interview, part one|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=October 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the prequel ''Yakuza 0'' Sega wanted to make Majima stand out from the Kiryu as in this title the two share the role of protagonists. Sega described Kiryu as a \"straight man trait \u2013 tough but honorable and keeps to himself a bit\" implying there are not too many difficulties in writing him. Through this game and the remake of the first game, ''Kiwami'', the relationship between Kiryu and Majima becomes more explored in contrast to the initial game of the franchise, most notably because of the changes made to Majima's characterization and the way he sees Kiryu's actions while being both friends and enemies at the same time. ''Yakuza 0'' also served as a story of Kiryu that Sega wanted players to know before reaching ''Yakuza 6''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2017/02/21/sega-on-the-challenges-of-bringing-yakuza-0-west.aspx|title=How Sega Brought Yakuza 0 To The West|date=February 21, 2017|magazine=Game Informer|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Gwaltney, Javy}}</ref> Kiryu's traits in ''Yakuza 0'' were specifically changed to a \"loose-cannon hot-head\" to the point long time fans would be surprised by his actions. However, chief Masayoshi Yokoyama stated the character would mature across the storyline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/the-yakuza-prequel-was-a-long-time-coming-1627835600|title=The Yakuza Prequel Was a Long Time Coming|date=August 28, 2014|website=Kotaku|accessdate=October 30, 2017|author=Nakamura, Toshi}}</ref> Despite Kiryu's fame, Sato noted that players ended up enjoying Majima far more in the franchise.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/e3-2018/2018/06/13/yakuzas-producer-discusses-possibility-of-a-majima-spin-off|title=Yakuza's Producer Discusses Possibility Of A Majima Spin-Off|magazine=Game Informer|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring development of ''Yakuza 4'', the staff started wondering how would they end Kiryu's story as, unlike other video game characters, he did not possess supernatural powers. They compared the character with [[James Bond]] whose actor changed multiple times across his movies. Describing him as \"a super-cool and masculine guy, but since he's a well-established character with a specific personality, there are things that he would and wouldn't do\" the team decided he would need a successor who would bring the staff more creativity to work with.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/yakuza-creator-talks-007-inspirations-wacky-humor-/1100-6451146/|title=Yakuza Creator Talks 007 Inspirations, Wacky Humor, And What's Next|website=GameSpot|accessdate=October 28, 2017|date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> In late 2016, Nagoshi claimed he had been doing Kazuma's story for nearly a decade, stating \"it had its pros and cons\". He concluded saying \"I also think that's a way to give back to Kazuma Kiryu. Sooner or later, I want to announce something different.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2016/12/4gamer-interviews-japanese-creators-2017-ambitions|title=4Gamer interviews Japanese creators on 2017 ambitions|publisher=Gematsu|date=December 27, 2016|accessdate=December 28, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228022701/http://gematsu.com/2016/12/4gamer-interviews-japanese-creators-2017-ambitions|archivedate=December 28, 2016}}</ref> In April 2017 Sega confirmed that while ''Yakuza 6'' will end Kiryu's story, the series will still go on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/170178-Yakuza-Game-in-The-Works|title=A New Yakuza Game is in The Works|publisher=Escapist|date=April 21, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017|author=Bogos, Steven}}</ref> Deciding to bring the last tale Kiryu with ''Yakuza 6'', the staff wanted to do the game as appealing as possible.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Famitsu|date=July 28, 2016|language=Japanese|transcript=http://yakuzafan.com/nagoshi-san-famitsu-interview/}}</ref> The game focuses on the family relationship between Kiryu and Haruka after years of being separated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gematsu.com/2017/11/yakuza-6-song-life-previously-yakuza-trailer-launch-edition-box-art|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life \u2018Previously on Yakuza\u2026\u2019 trailer, launch edition box art|publisher=Gematsu|date=November 16, 2017|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Voice actors===\nEnglish voice actor [[Darryl Kurylo]] said that he wanted to sound as good as possible after being impressed by the characterization of Kiryu and the lines he had to give. However, he regrets some lines were lost in translation of the original game. Nevertheless, Kurylo enjoyed the experience to the point of playing the game multiple times alongside his son. In order to fit the lipsyncing from the original Japanese game, Kurylo often had to say a line in different styles. Kurylo still found more fun when doing the yells for the fight scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tojohq.github.io/interview-darryl-kurylo/|title=TojoHQ Interviews - Darryl Kurylo|publisher=TojoHQ|accessdate=September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nNogashi was impressed by Kiryu's Japanese voice actor, [[Takaya Kuroda]], due to how he sang in the music minigame. Another staff member, Sato, was impressed by the karaoke game as it helped to show a fun side of Kiryu.<ref name=\"kuroda\">{{cite book|title=Ryu ga Gotoku 3 Guidebook|pages=522\u2013527}}</ref> Kuroda highly enjoyed voicing his character, being anxious in most scenes regardless of the tone he had to make. As a result, he wants to keep Kiryu in character. Kuroda describes Kiryu as a true shy character, stating he does not consider himself too attractive to the point he could not form a formal romantic relationship with Sayama in ''Yakuza 2''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsbeezer.com/franceeng/interview-with-daisuke-sato-and-takaya-kuroda/|title=TojoHQ Interviews - Darryl Kurylo|publisher=News Beezer|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n{{expand section|date=October 2017}}\n\n===''Yakuza''===\n{{main article|Yakuza (video game)|Yakuza Kiwami}}\nKiryu is a famous member of the Tojo clan, who earned the nickname of {{Nihongo|\"the Dragon of Dojima\"|\u5802\u5cf6\u306e\u9f8d|D\u014djima no Ry\u016b}}. Early in the first game he was planning on starting his own subsidiary group until he takes the blame for the murder of his boss, Sohei Dojima, to protect his best friend, Akira Nishikiyama, and is imprisoned for ten years.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Yakuza 2|publisher=Sega|quote=Kiryu: I was sentenced to ten years. After going inside I got a letter of expulsion from the Dojima Family and found out Yumi had disappeared.|developer=Sega}}</ref> After his release, Kiryu returns to his home town, Kamurocho, but due to his patricide he is marked for death by the entire [[yakuza]] community. Kiryu then learns that 10 billion yen has been stolen from the Tojo Clan. Soon after he meets a young girl called Haruka, whom seemingly every criminal group in the country is after. With help of detective Date, Kiryu manages to learn the truth of the money. Upon reuniting with Yumi, his childhood love and Haruka's mother he is confronted by Kyohei Jingu, Haruka's father, and the true owner of the money. After defeating Jingu, Kiryu is reunited with his old friend Nishiki. The two fight, with Kiryu coming out victorious. Jingu tries to shoot Kiryu but Yumi takes the bullet for him. Nishikiyama then kills himself with Jingu. After Yumi dies in Kiryu's arms, Kiryu subsequently decides to start a new, honest life with Haruka.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Yakuza 2|publisher=Sega|quote=Date: Snap out of it! You've still got something to fight for! There's someone who needs you! Don't run from your responsibilities!|developer=Sega}}</ref>\n\n===''Yakuza 2''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 2|Yakuza Kiwami 2}}\nIn ''[[Yakuza 2]]'', the fifth Chairman of the Tojo Clan, Yukio Terada, is assassinated and Kazuma Kiryu wants Sohei Dojima's son Daigo to take the clan's leadership and prevent an upcoming yakuza families war. While attempting to broker a peace deal between the Tojo and the Omi, Daigo and Jin Goda, Omi chairman, are kidnapped by Ryuji Goda, Jin's adopted son. Ryuji, through working with the Jingweon mafia, attempts to destroy Kamurocho and Kiryu to be the only dragon in Japan. Kiryu is put under the protective custody of a female detective called Kaoru Sayama, who uses him to get close to the Tojo to discover her past. Eventually, Kiryu and Ryuji fight atop Kamurocho Hills. Kiryu is victorious, but Yukio Terada appears, revealing that he faked his own death to start a war and is really a Jingweon survivor. Terada is also defeated, but begs Kiryu to trust him. After Jin Goda, Takashima and Terada are dead, Kiryu and Ryuji have a final showdown, which Kiryu wins. A bomb Terada had triggered, but secretly removed the fuse from, fails to detonate, saving Kiryu and Kaoru's lives.\n\n===''Yakuza 3''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 3}}\nFor ''[[Yakuza 3]]'' Kiryu leaves Kamurocho for [[Okinawa]], where he now runs the Morning Glory Orphanage. There he raises nine children, including Haruka Sawamura. He is caught up in a government plot when Morning Glory's land is in the way of a proposed resort.\n\n===''Yakuza 4''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 4}}\nDuring ''[[Yakuza 4]]'', Kiryu continues to run the orphanage. However, he is once again involved in the matters back in Kamurocho, having found Saejima washed ashore one day. Saejima tells him a man called Hamazaki told him to find Kiryu. Some time after Saejima leaves, Hamazaki washes ashore. After meeting up with Yasuko, Hamazaki sends the two on ahead to Kamurocho. There Kiryu leaves Yasuko at New Serena, but returns to find her missing after witness [[Goro Majima]] being arrested and dragged away from Millennium Tower to police patrol cars. He chases her into the sewers, where Tanimura and Akiyama mistake him for an Ueno Seiwa Clan member, and attack. After defeating them Kiryu chases Yasuko to the roof, where he finds her and Saejima bound and gagged by Katsuragi. During the events that follow Yasuko is shot and kills Katsuragi before dying herself. Kiryu later fights Daigo on top of the Millennium Tower.\n\n===''Yakuza 5''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 5}}\nIn ''[[Yakuza 5]]'', Kiryu has left the orphanage in Okinawa and becomes a taxi driver in Fukuoka under a false identity.\n\n===''Yakuza 6: The Song of Life''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 6: The Song of Life}}\nIn ''[[Yakuza 6: The Song of Life]]'', ex-idol and daughter figure to series protagonist Kazuma Kiryu, Haruka Sawamura, is involved in a mysterious hit-and-run. Finding out who is responsible takes Kiryu reluctantly back into the extra-judicial underbelly of Japan \u2014 Kamurocho, as well as a small fishing town near Hiroshima called Onomichi. Yakuza 6 is the final chapter in Kiryu's saga and closes out his story.\n\n===''Yakuza 0''===\n{{main article|Yakuza 0}}\nSeventeen years prior to the events of the first game, Kiryu is framed for killing a civilian during a routine debt collection and must find the true killer before his family is forced to take responsibility on his behalf. While he attempts to uncover the mysteries behind the murder, he becomes entangled in a ruthless real estate war.\n\n===''Yakuza: Like a Dragon''===\nWhile not its main protagonist, Kiryu is scheduled to appear in the upcoming ''[[Yakuza: Like a Dragon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cryer|first=Hirun|title=It Looks Like Kiryu Kazuma is Back for Yakuza 7|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/kiryu-kazuma-appears-to-return-for-yakuza-7|website=USGamer|date=November 13, 2019|accessdate=November 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Spinoffs and other appearances===\n[[File:Masakatsu Funaki.jpg|thumb|Masakatsu Funaki portrays Kiryu in the first film of the series.]]\nDuring the events of the zombie spinoff ''[[Yakuza: Dead Souls]]'', he returns to Kamurocho after Haruka is kidnapped by a mysterious man. In the film adaptation ''[[Like a Dragon: Prologue]]'', he is portrayed by [[Masakatsu Funaki]]. This film serves as a prequel of the first ''Yakuza'' game describing Kiryu's youth where he meets recurring characters from the series. As he grows up, Kiryu starts desiring to form his own group, but gives up on this when his girlfriend is sexually assaulted and he decides to take the blame for killing the person to protect Nishikiyama. In the film, ''[[Like a Dragon]]'', an adaptation of the first ''Yakuza'' game, he is portrayed by  [[Kazuki Kitamura]]. In the ''Yakuza'' stage show, he is portrayed by Eiji Takigawa.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-04-13/yakuza-stage-play-leads-photographed-in-costume/.87090|title=Yakuza Stage Play's Leads Photographed in Costume|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=April 13, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414044009/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-04-13/yakuza-stage-play-leads-photographed-in-costume/.87090|archivedate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOutside the ''Yakuza'' series, Kiryu appears as a guest character in ''[[Binary Domain]]'' through an unlockable code and ''[[Everybody's Golf 6]]'' through downloadable content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-stealths-binary-domain/|title=Yakuza's Kazuma Kiryu stealths into Binary Domain|publisher=GamesRadar|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515153936/http://www.gamesradar.com/yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-stealths-binary-domain/|archivedate=May 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2013/04/kazuma-kiryu-coming-to-hot-shots-golf-world-invitational|title=Kazuma Kiryu coming to Hot Shots Golf: World Invitational|publisher=Gematsu|date=April 17, 2013|accessdate=July 30, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816124950/http://gematsu.com/2013/04/kazuma-kiryu-coming-to-hot-shots-golf-world-invitational|archivedate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> He is also a playable in ''[[Project X Zone 2]]'' alongside Majima.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2015/04/12/project-x-zone-2-coming-west-fall/ |title=Project X Zone 2 Is Coming To The West This Fall |publisher=Siliconera |accessdate=April 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150414205701/http://www.siliconera.com/2015/04/12/project-x-zone-2-coming-west-fall/ |archivedate=April 14, 2015 }}</ref> In ''[[Fist of the North Star: Lost Paradise]]'', a ''Yakuza'' spinoff based on ''[[Fist of the North Star]]'', Kiryu appears as a [[skin (video gaming)|skin]] for [[Kenshiro]] via downloadable content.<ref>https://www.destructoid.com/fist-of-the-north-star-s-kiryu-dlc-will-be-free-for-two-weeks-522567.phtml</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical===\nCritical reception to Kiryu's character has been generally positive. Juan Castro from [[IGN]] praised him as an appealing character noting, both his violent traits as well as his kindness. They further noted that while being a \"badass\", he stands out thanks to his kindness.<ref name=\"ignreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/06/yakuza-review|title=Yakuza review|date=September 6, 2006|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226222214/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/06/yakuza-review|archivedate=February 26, 2014}}</ref> The same website listed him as a notorious anti-hero as he \"walks a fine line between good and bad.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/03/05/gamings-most-notorious-anti-heroes?page=4|title=GAMING'S MOST NOTORIOUS ANTI-HEROES|website=IGN|accessdate=May 20, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317012423/http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/03/05/gamings-most-notorious-anti-heroes?page=4|archivedate=March 17, 2014}}</ref> Cheat Code Central expressed similar comments noting that despite the character's occupation, he is so kind he takes the blame of Dojima's death in the start of the first game resulting in the expulsion from his family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cheatcc.com/psx2/rev/yakuzareview.html#ixzz2xFtxSCWe|title=Yakuza review|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328211911/http://www.cheatcc.com/psx2/rev/yakuzareview.html#ixzz2xFtxSCWe|archivedate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> [[Eurogamer]] similarly commented that \"Despite all the violence, Kazuma is quite a personable bloke, whose love for his friends sees him banged up for ten years over a murder his 'brother' Nishiki committed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_yakuza_ps2|title=Yakuza review|website=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226163827/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/r_yakuza_ps2|archivedate=February 26, 2014}}</ref> VideoGamer.com's Wesley Yin-Poole also shared similar commenting adding that \" Kazuma isn't averse to the odd spot of humanitarian work either - he's just a big softy really.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps2/yakuza/review.html|title=Yakuza Review|publisher=VideoGamer.com|date=September 28, 2006|author=Yin-Poole, Wesley|accessdate=March 28, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328204610/http://www.videogamer.com/ps2/yakuza/review.html|archivedate=March 28, 2014}}</ref> Greg Orlando from the magazine ''[[Newtype]]'' found him entertaining due to multiple actions he does across the series.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Orlando |first=Greg |url=http://www.newtype-usa.com/reviews/index.php?itemid=315 |title=Yakuza |work=Newtype USA |volume=5 |issue=9 |date=September 2006 |issn=1541-4817 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061124041801/http://www.newtype-usa.com/reviews/index.php?itemid=315 |archivedate=November 24, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> When reviewing ''Yakuza 3'', Sam Marchello from RPGamer noted the character's notable development comparing his life with the Yakuza to the orphans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpgamer.com/games/yakuza/yakuza3/reviews/yakuza3strev1.html|title=Yakuza 3 - Staff Review|publisher=RPGamer.com|author=Marchello, Sam|accessdate=March 29, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330004901/http://www.rpgamer.com/games/yakuza/yakuza3/reviews/yakuza3strev1.html|archivedate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> Greg Miller from IGN noted how developers wanted players to connect to Kiryu's side in ''Yakuza 3'' as a result of being his motivation, resulting in several cutscenes and minigames which left him mixed feelings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/09/yakuza-3-review?page=2|title=Yakuza 3 Review|website=IGN|author=Miller, Greg|accessdate=March 29, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330054709/http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/03/09/yakuza-3-review?page=2|archivedate=March 30, 2014}}</ref> Anthony John Agnello from [[GamesRadar]] praised Kiryu's initial appearance alongside his personality.<ref>{{cite web|title=Why I Love: Kazuma Kiryu's suit in Yakuza|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/why-i-love-kazuma-kiryus-suit-yakuza/|accessdate=April 16, 2016|author=Agnello, Anthony John|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|date=December 18, 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924164945/http://www.gamesradar.com/why-i-love-kazuma-kiryus-suit-yakuza/|archivedate=September 24, 2016}}</ref> Matt Kim from US Gamer said Kiryu was his favorite paternal figure in gaming due to how caring he is to Haruka and to people in general despite his connections with the yakuza.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/community-question-whos-your-favorite-dad-in-video-games|title=Who's Your Favorite Dad in Video Games?|publisher=US Gamer|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Push Square listed him as one of the best characters seen in PlayStation games based on his skills in combat and sense of justice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2017/01/feature_5_reasons_why_kazuma_kiryu_is_the_hardest_man_on_playstation|title=Feature: 5 Reasons Why Kazuma Kiryu Is the Hardest Man on PlayStation|publisher=Push Square|accessdate=June 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn a more critical view, [[Greg Kasavin]] from [[GameSpot]] stated that while Kiryu often resorts to profanity \"he's your prototypical hero taking on your prototypical villains.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yakuza review|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-review/1900-6157009/|accessdate=March 28, 2014|website=GameSpot|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208032949/http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-review/1900-6157009/|archivedate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> [[1UP.com]] called him \"a hard-boiled thug\" comparing him with characters like [[Niko Bellic|Niko]] and [[Alex Mercer (Prototype)|Alex Mercer]] due to his inhuman powers. They further noted that his powers can be \"ridiculous.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberty for All: How We Arrived at GTA4, Infamous, and Prototype|url=http://www.1up.com/features/liberty-arrived-gta4-infamous-prototype?pager.offset=2|accessdate=October 7, 2015|website=1UP.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608165721/http://www.1up.com/features/liberty-arrived-gta4-infamous-prototype?pager.offset=2|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> Real life yakuza Midoriyama commented on the character during a review of the third game that \"Kiryu is the way yakuza used to be. We kept the streets clean. People liked us. We didn't bother ordinary citizens. We respected our bosses. Now, guys like that only exist in video games.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yakuza 3 reviewed by Yakuza|url=http://boingboing.net/2010/08/10/yakuza-3-review.html|accessdate=March 28, 2014|publisher=BoingBoing|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140208192152/http://boingboing.net/2010/08/10/yakuza-3-review.html|archivedate=February 8, 2014}}</ref> In a ''[[Famitsu]]'' poll from 2010, Kiryu was voted as the eleventh best video game character.<ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Snake Beats Mario, Is Coolest Video Game Character Ever\n |url         = http://www.1up.com/news/snake-beats-mario-coolest-video\n |date        = February 10, 2010\n |accessdate  = October 7, 2015\n |website   = 1UP.com\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/6i8KLI3kn?url=http://www.1up.com/news/snake-beats-mario-coolest-video\n |archivedate = 2016-06-09\n}}</ref> In a retrospective of the series, GameSpot compared Kiryu with [[Michael Corleone]], the protagonist of the novel ''[[The Godfather (novel)|The Godfather]]'' by [[Mario Puzo]]. GameSpot noted that while Kiryu was featured with pacifistic traits as he wishes to have a peaceful life with Haruka, he still has violent traits as he has no problems with beating up enemies across the series. In addition to Kiryu's story, the site also commented on how well developed were from clunky to more unique as latter games in the franchise included new characters with different fighting styles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/amp-articles/the-history-of-yakuza/1100-6456703/|title=The History Of Yakuza|date=February 10, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2018|website=GameSpot}}</ref> \n\nCritics have also noted Kiryu was handled different in the prequel ''Yakuza 0'' and had mixed feelings on its execution. [[Anime News Network]] writer Dustin Bailey praised Kiryu's role in ''Yakuza 0'' saying that while in most of the games he was portrayed as a \"saintly [[Superman]]\", in the prequel he enjoyed seeing the character involved in darker scenarios.<ref>{{cite news|title=This Week in Games - Yakuza 0|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-x-button/2017-02-02/this-week-in-games-yakuza-0/.111745|accessdate=February 3, 2017|date=February 2, 2017|author=Bailey, Dustin|work=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202183251/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/the-x-button/2017-02-02/this-week-in-games-yakuza-0/.111745|archivedate=February 2, 2017}}</ref> As a result, he found the PlayStation 3 ''Yakuza'' games less interesting due to a focus on Kiryu's struggle for a peaceful life, but, conversely, found ''Yakuza 5'' to be more unique due to its inclusion of bizarre enemies for Kiryu to fight, most notably a bear.<ref>{{cite news|title=Everything You Need to Know About Yakuza|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2017-08-25/everything-you-need-to-know-about-yakuza/.119814|accessdate=August 25, 2017|date=August 25, 2017|author=Bailey, Dustin|work=[[Anime News Network]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170828203548/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2017-08-25/everything-you-need-to-know-about-yakuza/.119814|archivedate=August 28, 2017}}</ref> Due to Majima showing a different characterization in the prequel, writers found him as a better character than Kiryu.finding him more interesting than Kiryu.<ref name=\"des\">{{cite web |last=Glagowski |first=Peter |date=19 January 2017 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-0-412494.phtml |title=Review: Yakuza 0 |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119183035/https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-0-412494.phtml |archivedate=January 19, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"egmno\">{{cite magazine |last=Plessas |first=Nick |date=January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |title=Yakuza 0 review |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121013119/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cork |first=Jeff |date= January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_0/b/playstation4/archive/2017/01/19/everlasting-mob-stopper.aspx |title=Everlasting Mob Stopper - Yakuza 0 - PlayStation 4 |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170120022852/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_0/b/playstation4/archive/2017/01/19/everlasting-mob-stopper.aspx |archivedate=January 20, 2017}}</ref> '[[EGMNOW]]'' liked the contrast the duo had in the narrative because of the different quests they had to pass to achieve their goals.<ref name=\"egmno\">{{cite magazine |last=Plessas |first=Nick |date=January 19, 2017 |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |title=Yakuza 0 review |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |accessdate=January 19, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170121013119/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/yakuza-0-review/ |archivedate=January 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Jimquisition]]'' said that both characters were \"like-able protagonists who consistently have to act as straight men in a variety of weird situations\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Sterling |first=Jim |date=19 January 2017 |url=http://www.thejimquisition.com/yakuza-0-review/ |title=Yakuza 0 Review \u2013 Majimagnificent |publisher=[[The Jimquisition]] |accessdate=January 27, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170127005102/http://www.thejimquisition.com/yakuza-0-review/ |archivedate=January 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs multiple games involved Kiryu returning to the yakuza life despite his retirement in the first game, ''USGamer'' criticized this recycling format and expected ''Yakuza 6'' follow the true end of Kiryu's arc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/everything-you-need-to-know-about-the-yakuza-series-before-yakuza-6|title=A Yakuza Primer: Everything You Need to Know About the Series Before Yakuza 6\n|accessdate=April 13, 2020|publisher=US Gamer}}</ref> For the review of ''Yakuza 6: The Song of Life'', UK Anime Network believed Sega managed to close Kiryu's story in an appealing despite his interactions with Haruto, an infant Kiryu looks after across the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/games/Yakuza_6:_The_Song_of_Life.html|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life|date=|accessdate=June 21, 2018|publisher=UK Anime Network}}</ref> Destructoid liked the handling of Kiryu, due to his more serious personality caused by Haruka's crisis.<ref name=\"Destructoid\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-492903.phtml|title=Review: Yakuza 6: The Song of Life|last=Glagowski|first=Peter|website=[[Destructoid]]|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318053355/https://www.destructoid.com/review-yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-492903.phtml|archivedate=18 March 2018}}</ref> GameInformer felt that the narrative gave the character an appropiate closure even if it is sad.<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_6_the_song_of_life/b/playstation4/archive/2018/03/15/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-game-informer-review.aspx|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life review|last=Cork|first=Jeff|magazine=[[Game Informer]]|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=28 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323223235/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/yakuza_6_the_song_of_life/b/playstation4/archive/2018/03/15/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-game-informer-review.aspx|archivedate=23 March 2018}}</ref> GameRevolution shared similar comments, mainly on how Haruka also has been developing in previous games to stay close to her adoptive father and it was this time Kiryu's quest to protect her.<ref name=\"GameRev\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/376091-yakuza-6-review-like-a-dragon|title=Yakuza 6 Review: Like a Dragon|last=Faulkner|first=Jason|publisher=[[Game Revolution]]|date=15 March 2016|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315140231/http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/376091-yakuza-6-review-like-a-dragon|archivedate=15 March 2018}}</ref> GameSpot noted the game touched deep themes as Kiryu often interacted with families, making it fitting for his final game with him as the main character.<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-review-a-hard-boiled-old/1900-6416875/|title=Yakuza 6: The Song of Life Review|last=Tran|first=Edmond|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=16 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318053352/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/yakuza-6-the-song-of-life-review-a-hard-boiled-old/1900-6416875/|archivedate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Popularity===\nIn a popularity poll from 2018 by Sega, Kiryu took the 2nd position behind Goro Majima.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/09/28/yakuza-series-popularity-poll-shows-its-current-top-20-favorite-characters/|title=Yakuza Series Popularity Poll Shows Its Current Top-20 Favorite Characters|publisher=Siliconera|accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> Because ''Yakuza'' has a long running history of being [[PlayStation]] exclusive, Kazuma Kiryu is often recognized as a PlayStation mascot.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Playstation Mascots|url=http://watchmojo.com/suggest/Top+10+Playstation+Mascots|publisher=Watchmojo|accessdate=1 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141125131514/http://watchmojo.com/suggest/Top+10+Playstation+Mascots|archivedate=25 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=25 Characters That Need to Be in \u2018PlayStation All-Stars Battle Royale\u2019|url=http://gamerant.com/playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-characters-wishlist-riley-145888/|last=Little|first=Riley|publisher=Gamerant|accessdate=1 February 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201011041/http://gamerant.com/playstation-all-stars-battle-royale-characters-wishlist-riley-145888/|archivedate=1 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn promoting [[Kai Razor]] and ''[[Yakuza: Dead Souls]]'', Kiryu's image was used in the razor. Kiryu also uses such razor during a scene from ''Of the End''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kai Razor Makes Yakuza's Kazuma Kiryu The Best He Can Get|url=http://andriasang.com/comu8o/yakuza_shaver/|accessdate=March 28, 2014|publisher=Andriasang|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413200226/http://andriasang.com/comu8o/yakuza_shaver/|archivedate=April 13, 2014}}</ref> Sega also sponsored a contest where the winner would get Kiryu's $9000 tattoo. The winner was Fari Salievski. The process took sixth months to complete. Salivevski commented \"Well, my nickname is now \"The Dragon\"... Whilst in Thailand, I had people coming up to me and taking photos, other cam round wondering what all the fuss was about thinking I am some kind of celebrity. I could not stop laughing! my Facebook page gets a lot of comments too.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Man Wins Kazuma Kiryu's $9000 Back Tattoo|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/man-wins-kazuma-kiryus-9000-back-tattoo-4783|accessdate=March 28, 2014|publisher=GameRevolution|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817205934/http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/man-wins-kazuma-kiryus-9000-back-tattoo-4783|archivedate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nKazuma Kiryu was requested as a guest character in Bandai Namco's [[fighting game]] ''[[Tekken 7]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Harada on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853769649447608320|website=Twitter|accessdate=22 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422203438/https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853769649447608320|archivedate=22 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Harada on Twitter|url=https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853951496349663232?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http%3A%2F%2Fyakuzafan.com%2Fkazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc%2F|website=Twitter|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171022150154/https://twitter.com/Harada_TEKKEN/status/853951496349663232?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http%3A%2F%2Fyakuzafan.com%2Fkazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc%2F|archivedate=22 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Here are the top guest characters suggested to Katsuhiro Harada for Tekken 7|url=http://tekkengamer.com/2017/04/18/top-guest-characters-suggested-katsuhiro-harada-tekken-7/|website=Tekkengamer|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420235616/http://tekkengamer.com/2017/04/18/top-guest-characters-suggested-katsuhiro-harada-tekken-7/|archivedate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ross|first1=Deacon|title=Kazuma Kiryu Most Requested Character For Tekken 7 DLC!|url=http://yakuzafan.com/kazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc/|website=Yakuzafan|accessdate=20 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420144324/http://yakuzafan.com/kazuma-kiryu-requested-character-tekken-7-dlc/|archivedate=20 April 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Miche|first1=Hunter|title=Kazuma Kiryu Is The Most Requested Tekken 7 Guest Character|url=http://segmentnext.com/2017/04/22/kazuma-kiryu-requested-tekken-7-guest-character/|website=Segmentnext|accessdate=21 April 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.