ks-rage-quitting-possible-nintend/1100-6449617/|archivedate=26 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Why Yakuza\u2019s Kazuma Kiryu should be in Tekken 7|url=http://segabits.com/blog/2017/05/02/why-yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-should-be-in-tekken-7/|website=Segabits|accessdate=3 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170503114451/http://segabits.com/blog/2017/05/02/why-yakuzas-kazuma-kiryu-should-be-in-tekken-7/|archivedate=3 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Orselli|first1=Brandon|title=TEKKEN 7 PRODUCER ASKS FANS WHAT GUEST CHARACTERS SHOULD APPEAR IN GAME|url=http://nichegamer.com/2017/04/24/tekken-7-producer-asks-fans-what-guest-characters-should-appear-in-game/|website=Nichegamer|accessdate=3 May 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516154038/http://nichegamer.com/2017/04/24/tekken-7-producer-asks-fans-what-guest-characters-should-appear-in-game/|archivedate=16 May 2017}}</ref> Even after the revealed guest characters were [[Geese Howard]] and [[Noctis Lucis Caelum]], fans took to Twitter to express their enthusiasm in having Kiryu included in the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ashcraft|first1=Bryan|title=Forget Noctis, Here Are Other Ideas For Tekken 7 Characters|url=https://kotaku.com/forget-noctis-here-are-other-ideas-for-tekken-7-charac-1820424912|website=Kotaku|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref> ''Yakuza'' producer Daisuke Sato stated that \"As far as it comes down to the whole ''Tekken'' thing, if Harada-san actually says he wants to use Kiryu, then hey.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Yakuza Producer says if Harada wants Kazuma Kiryu in Tekken 7, they\u2019re for it|url=http://segabits.com/blog/2018/03/18/yakuza-producer-says-if-harada-wants-kazuma-kiryu-in-tekken-7-theyre-for-it/|website=Segabits|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rinaldi|first1=Casey|title=Yakuza series Producer Daisuke Sato says it\u2019s up to Harada if fans want to see Kazuma Kiryu in Tekken 7|url=http://shoryuken.com/2018/03/21/yakuza-series-producer-daisuke-sato-says-its-up-to-harada-if-fans-want-to-see-kazuma-kiryu-in-tekken-7/|website=Shoryuken|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=M\u00e4ki|first1=Jonas|title=Bandai Namco are free to use Kazuma Kiryu in Tekken 7|url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/news/646243/Bandai+Namco+are+free+to+use+Kazuma+Kiryu+in+Tekken+7/|website=Gamereactor|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Yakuza series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiryu, Kazuma}}\n[[Category:Action-adventure game characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional criminals in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional Japanese people in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional male martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional martial artists in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Fictional taxicab drivers]]\n[[Category:Fictional yakuza]]\n[[Category:Male characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Sega protagonists]]\n[[Category:Video game characters introduced in 2005]]\n[[Category:Vigilante characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Yakuza (series)]]\n", "name_user": "Tintor2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCreation and development", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazuma_Kiryu"}
{"title_page": "List of shipwrecks in August 1863", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in August 1863''' includes ships sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during August [[1863]].\n{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n\n==1 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Georgia|1863|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground off [[Nantucket]], [[Massachusetts]], United States. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=LM240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jeune Frederick'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[lugger]] sank {{convert|4|nmi|km}} north east of [[Abrevach]], [[Finist\u00e8re]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Fontarabia]], Spain.<ref name=LM110863/><ref name=S110863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Storm Cloud'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashoyre at [[Akyab]], [[British Burma|Burma]] and broke in two. She was on a voyage from Akyab to a European port.<ref name=S180963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unnamed \n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The ship was sunk off [[Charleston, South Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]] by {{USS|New Ironsides}} ({{navy|USA|1863}}) with the loss of all hands.<ref name=CM220863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=22 August 1863 |issue=23129 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Coriolanus''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sprang a leak and was beached on [[Langlade Island]], where she became a wreck. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Miramichi, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]<ref name=Times010963/><ref name=GH020963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=2 September 1863 |issue=7378 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Idalia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore on [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]], Sweden. She was on a voyage from [[Vyborg]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]] to [[West Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]]. She was refloated and taken in to \"Ekwik\" in a waterlogged condition.<ref name=S110863/><ref name=NC140863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Eglington''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground on the Aceitera Flats, off [[Cape Trafalgar]], Spain. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=Times100863>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Bombay and Mauritius Mails |date=10 August 1863 |page_number=7 |issue=24633 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date3= August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Halcyon'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] foundered off [[Great Cumbrae Island]], [[Argyllshire]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[Ardrossan]], [[Ayrshire]] to [[Newry]], [[County Antrim]].<ref name=DC080863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''St. Vincent'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Hannah Secor'' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''St. Vincent'' was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], [[Virgin Islands]].<ref name=LM070863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=7 August 1863 |issue=4834 }}</ref><ref name=CM080863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=8 August 1863 |issue=23117 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Georgia|1863|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground and was wrecked at [[Cape Sable Island]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]]. All on board were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=Times290863>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Americe |date=29 August 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24650 |column=B-D }}</ref><ref name=Georgia>{{cite web |url=http://www.tynebuiltships.co.uk/G-Ships/georgia1863.html |title=Georgia |publisher=Shipping & Shipbuilding Research Trust |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gulterus'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] struck an [[iceberg]] in the Atlantic Ocean. She was set afire and abandoned by her crew, who were rescued by the [[schooner]] ''Prince'' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Jersey]]. ''Gulterus'' was on a voyage from [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to Liverpool.<ref name=LM040963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=4 September 1863 |issue=4858 }}</ref><ref name=CM050963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=5 September 1863 |issue=23141 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ruth''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 702-ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] was set afire by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] agents on the [[Mississippi River]] at [[Lucas Bend]], {{convert|4|nmi|km}} below [[Norfolk, Missouri]]. She was engulfed in flames within five minutes and burned for five hours before sinking in {{convert|18|ft|m}} of water. Thirty lives were lost. Her wreck was blown up with [[gunpowder]] on 19 October.<ref name=gainesp102>Gaines, p. 102.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Union Packet'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore on [[Sheep Island, Pembrokeshire]] and was abandoned by her crew. She was refloated with assistance from the smack ''Amity'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and taken in to [[Milford Haven]], [[Pembrokeshire]], where she sank.<ref name=CM080863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anglo-Saxon'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Her twelve crew were rescued by ''Reciprocity'' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[British North America]]) ''Anglo-Saxon'' was on a voyage from [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], British North America to [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]].<ref name=S220863/><ref name=NC280863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Barclay'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship struck a rock off [[Swinem\u00fcnde]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] and was damaged.<ref name=CM080863/> She was on a voyage from Swinem\u00fcnde to [[London]]. She consequently put in to [[Stettin]].<ref name=DC080863>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=8 August 1863 |issue=3119 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cheshire'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground and was wrecked at [[Musquash, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]]. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Saint John, New Brunswick]].<ref name=LM240863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=24 August 1863 |issue=4848 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Paw Paw|1863|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The centerwheel [[paddle steamer]] sank within 15 minutes of striking a [[Snag (ecology)|snag]] in the [[Mississippi River]] near [[Hardin's Point]], [[Arkansas]]. She was refloated, repaired, and returned to service.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Storm Cloud'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was lost near [[Akyab]], [[British Burma|Burma]].<ref name=LM070963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=7 September 1863 |issue=4860 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rudolph'' \n|flag=[[File:Civil flag of Oldenburg.svg|22px]] [[Grand Duchy of Oldenburg]] \n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked at \"Dembeck\", near [[\u0141eba|Leba]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[Aberdeen]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].<ref name=LM140863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=14 August 1863 |issue=4840 }}</ref><ref name=CM150863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=15 August 1863 |issue=23123 }}</ref><ref name=AJ190863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=19 August 1863 |issue=6032 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Carleton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] sprang a leak and was beached at [[Harwich]], [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Seaham]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=S110863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=11 August 1863 |issue=12168 |page=7 }}</ref><ref name=NC140863>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=London |date=14 August 1863 |issue=9842 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Faith''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=Carrying a cargo of [[coal]] intended for [[United States Navy]] ships [[Union blockade|blockading]] [[Charleston, South Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]], the [[barque]] ran ashore and bilged off [[Port Royal, South Carolina]].<ref name=gainesp145>Gaines, p. 145.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Norfolk Hero'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Hermes Spit in the [[Gulf of Smyrna]]. She was on a voyage from [[Swansea]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Smyrna]], [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=S190863a/> She was refloated the next day and taken in to Smyrna.<ref name=S250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Spanish frigate|Petronila|1855|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Spain|1785}}\n|desc=The {{sclass-|Petronila|frigate}} was wrecked at [[Mariel, Cuba]]. Her crew survived.<ref name=Times190963>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The India, China, and Australian Mails |date=19 September 1863 |page_number=6 |issue=24668 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pico'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked in the [[Gut of Canso]]. She was on a voyage from [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States to [[Pictou]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]].<ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Secret'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was damaged by fire at [[Gothenburg]], Sweden.<ref name=S110863/> She was repaired and departed on 14 August for [[Bridgwater]], [[Somerset]].<ref name=S190863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==9 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=9 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cambria''\n|flag={{flag|Bremen}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] struck an [[iceberg]] in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. She was abandoned on 12 August and set afire. Her crew were rescued by ''Lotus'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Cambria'' was on a voyage from [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to the [[River Clyde|Clyde]].<ref name=Times250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Commodore'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The [[Steamship|steamer]] was lost south of [[Point Judith, Rhode Island|Point Judith]], [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=gainesp140>Gaines, p. 140.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gloucestershire''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] was partly abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] in a waterlogged condition. Twelve of her seventeen crew were taken off by the [[schooner]] ''Electric Spark'' ({{flag|United States|1863}}). ''Gloucestershire'' was on a voyage from [[Saint John, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times010963/><ref name=LM010963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=1 September 1863 |issue=4855 }}</ref><ref name=S010963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Helen Inglis'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked near \"Lakken\", Denmark. She was on a voyage from [[Grangemouth]], [[Stirlingshire]] to [[danzig|Dantsic]].<ref name=S170863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==10 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=10 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jeanette Melanie'' \n|flag={{flag|Belgium}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] foundered off [[Cabo da Roca]], Portugal. She was on a voyage from [[Lisbon]], Portugal to [[Ostend]], [[West Flanders]].<ref name=CM190863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jeune Adele'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked on a reef south east of [[Bermuda]]. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], [[Virgin Islands]].<ref name=S150963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hoppett'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was run ashore and wrecked at \"Ruberg\", Denmark. She was on a voyage from [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] to [[Cronstadt]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]].<ref name=LM130863/><ref name=NC140863/><ref name=S170863a/><ref name=NC210863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==11 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=11 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Beatitude'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship collided with another vessel in the [[Noordhollandsch Kanaal]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Amsterdam]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands. She was taken in to Amsterdam in a sinking condition. Subsequently placed under repair.<ref name=CM190863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercrury |location=Edinburgh |date=19 August 1863 |issue=23126 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sea Gull'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[New Zealand]]\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was struck by lightning off the coast of [[Taranaki]], destroying the mainmast and starting a fire. To save the lives of those on board, the skipper deliberately beached the ship near the mouth of the Henui River (Te Henui Stream, [[New Plymouth]]).<ref name=SNZD92>Ingram & Wheatley, p. 92.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==12 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{PS|Celt|1848|2}}, and<br>''Garibaldi'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Garibaldi'' collided with the [[paddle steamer]] ''Celt'' and sank in the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] at [[Port Glasgow]], [[Renfrewshire]]. Her two crew were rescued. ''Celt'' ran aground. Her passengers were taken off by another steamshis.<ref name=AJ190863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck 