n{{shipwreck list begin |date=17 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Crocus|1862|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The armed [[screw steamer]] was wrecked on [[Bodie Island|Bodie\u2032s Island]], [[North Carolina]], [[British North America]].<ref name=gainesp117>Gaines, p. 117.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Urania'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British North America]]\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the North Reef, off [[Antigua]]. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to Antigua. She was refloated.<ref name=CM160963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==18 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=18 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Cross Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Norfolk]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], United Kingdom to [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain. She was refloated and taken in to [[Great Yarmouth]], Norfolk in a leaky condition.<ref name=S190863a>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=19 August 1863 |issue=12175 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hebe''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: Pursued by the armed [[screw steamer]] {{USS|Niphon|1863|6}} and the armed sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] {{USS|Shokokon|1862|6}} (both {{navy|United States|1863}}), the screw steamer, carrying a cargo of [[coffee]], clothing, [[medicine]], and provisions, ran aground on [[Pleasure Island (North Carolina)|Federal Point]], north of [[Fort Fisher]], [[North Carolina]] and was abandoned by her crew. According to one source, the ''Shokokon'' then riddled her with gunfire, igniting a fire that burned her to the [[waterline]]. According to another source, six United States Navy warships shelled ''Hebe''\u2032s wreck on 20 August, destroying her machinery and completing her destruction.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863>[http://www.usnlp.org/navychronology/1863b.html usnlp.org Navy Chronology of the Civil War, July-December 1863]</ref><ref name=gainesp121>Gaines, p. 121.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Campbell'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] struck a sunken rock and foundered in the Sount of Callaway with the loss of two of her crew.<ref name=GH240863>{{Cite news |title=Greenock |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=24 August 1863 |issue=7370 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS Savannah (gunboat)|CSS ''Oconee'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=The [[gunboat]] foundered in bad weather in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] south of [[St. Catherines Island]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], during a voyage from [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], to [[England]] with a cargo of [[cotton]]. Her crew abandoned ship safely, but a [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] ship captured 15 of them off the coast of [[Florida]] on 20 August.<ref name=gainesp43>Gaines, p. 43.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ranger'' <!--not Hero-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Kilkee]], [[County Clare]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]].<ref name=LM210863/><ref name=CM220863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==19 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=19 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Clara Ellen'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at Soldier's Point. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Miramichi]], [[New Brunswick]], [[British North America]]. She was refloated on 27 August and taken in to [[Dundalk]], [[County Louth]] in a severely leaky condition.<ref name=S310863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ellen and Sarah'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[Mersey Flat]] collided with the [[pilot boat]] ''No. 9'' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank at [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]. She was refloated.<ref name=LM210863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=21 August 1863 |issue=4846 }}</ref><ref name=S220863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=22 August 1863 |issue=12178 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Helen Jane'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked at [[Aveiro, Portugal]] with the loss of one of her seven crew and one reported missing.<ref name=S220863/> She was on a voyage from [[Oporto]], Portugal to [[London]].<ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS Robert Habersham|CSS ''Robert Habersham'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=The 173- or 200-ton [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel]] [[Troop transport|transport]] suffered a [[boiler]] explosion on the [[Savannah River]] at [[Savannah, Georgia]], that wrecked her, injured at least eight to ten people, and may have killed her entire crew of 25.<ref name=gainesp50>Gaines, p. 50.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=x-XcAgWYTMMC&pg=PA180&lpg=PA180&dq=%22Robert+Habersham%22+explosion+August+1863&source=bl&ots=wTjDnPO3AF&sig=ix4uvnqsugAvtBwnAHKiNFW4hN4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvlbKFw4fWAhVBRWMKHcTkByMQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=Habersham&f=false Silverstone, Paul H., ''Civil War Navies, 1855-1883'', New York: Routledge/Taylor & Francis, 2006, {{ISBN|0-415-97870-X}}, p. 180.]</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Scout'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Jersey]]\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] ran aground at [[Gardenstown]], [[Aberdeenshire]].  She was refloated.<ref name=CM270863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==20 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=20 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Adelicia'' <!--not Salacia-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Horsey, Norfolk]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[Sunderland, County Durham]].<ref name=LM210863/><ref name=S220863/><ref name=S240863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=24 August 1863 |issue=12179 |page=8 }}</ref><ref name=NC280863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Bessy Bent'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Breaksea Point]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=LM240863/><ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Petit Corporal''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore on [[Anholt (Denmark)|Anholt]], Denmark.<ref name=Times250863/><ref name=LM250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William S. Bull''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The 16-ton [[screw steamer]] foundered in [[Lake Erie]] about 40 [[nautical mile]]s (74 km) from [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=gainesp56>Gaines, p. 56.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==21 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=21 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anglo Saxon''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 868-ton [[clipper]], bound from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], to [[New York City|New York]] with a cargo of [[coal]], was captured and burned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] near [[Brest, France|Brest]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Florida (cruiser)|CSS ''Florida'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}).<ref name=macslogflorida>[http://ahoy.tk-jk.net/MaraudersCivilWar/CSSFlorida.html Ahoy - Mac's Web Log \"Marauders of the Sea, Confederate Merchant Raiders During the American Civil War: CSS Florida. 1862-1863. Captain John Newland Maffitt. CSS Florida. 1864. Captain Charles M. Morris\"]</ref><ref name=\"usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863\" /><ref name=gainesp36>Gaines, p. 36.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anna Maria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Newcombe Sands, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Bainbridge|1842|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] capsized and sank in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Cape Hatteras]], [[North Carolina]]. Only two members of her crew survived the sinking to escape in a boat, but one of them became crazed, jumped overboard, and drowned. ''South Boston'' (flag unknown) rescued the only surviving crewman two days later.<ref name=gainesp114>Gaines, p. 114.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Benjamin R. Milan'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] foundered in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Thebes'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Benjamin R. Milan'' was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]] to [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain.<ref name=S180963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=18 September 1863 |issue=12201 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Champion''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 676-ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] was burned by Confederate agents on the [[Mississippi River]] at [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], [[Tennessee]], [[Confederate States of America]] with the loss of one life.<ref name=gainesp92>Gaines, p. 92.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Columbia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship|steam]] [[dredger]] sank in the [[English Channel]] {{convert|3|nmi|km}} east of [[Shoreham-by-Sea]], [[Sussex]]. Her crew were rescued. She was being towed from [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]] to Shoreham-by-Sea.<ref name=CM260863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=26 August 1863 |issue=23132 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Edmund Cooper'' <!--not Edward Cooper-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] struck the pier at [[Dover]], [[Kent]] and was beached.<ref name=S270863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=27 August 1863 |issue=12182 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Emanuel'' \n|flag=[[File:Merchant Ensign of Holstein-Gottorp (Lions sinister).svg|22px]] [[Duchy of Holstein]] \n|desc=The ship was run down and sunk in the North Sea by the [[steamshhip]] ''Chevy Chase'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). She was on a voyage from [[Elbing]] to [[Altona, Hamburg|Altona]].<ref name=S250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Fielding'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore on the [[Isle of Arran]]. She was on a voyage from [[Belfast]], [[County Antrim]] to [[Ardrossan]], [[Ayrshire]].<ref name=LM250863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=25 August 1863 |issue=4849 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Ellen'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] ran aground on the Kimmeridge Ledge, in the [[English Channel]] off the coast of [[Dorset]]. She was on a voyage from [[Middlesbrough]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]] to [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]]. She was refloated with assistance from the [[HM Coastguard|Coast Guard]].<ref name=CM270863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=27 August 1863 |issue=23133 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Reynolds'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground in Castlemaine Bay.<ref name=LM220863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=22 August 1863 |issue=4847 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Panuglios'' \n|flag={{flag|Ottoman Empire|naval-1844}}\n|desc=The [[lighter (barge)|lighter]] was run down and sunk near [[Tulcea]] by the [[steamship]] ''Taurib'' ({{flagcountry|Russian Empire}}). She was on a voyage from [[Izmail]] to [[Sulina]].<ref name=LM260863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=26 August 1863 |issue=4850 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Queen Mab'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship caught fire at New York and was scuttled on the Jersey Flats.<ref name=LM040963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==22 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=22 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Alexander Cooper''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The [[schooner]] was burned in [[New Topsail Inlet]] on the coast of [[North Carolina]] by a boat crew from the sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] {{USS|Shokokon|1862|6}} ({{navy|United States|1863}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Georges Creek''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The 448-ton [[screw steamer]] foundered in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Cape Hatteras]], North Carolina.<ref name=gainesp120>Gaines, p. 120.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentified schooner\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=American Civil War, Union blockade: The [[schooner]] was burned in New Topsail Inlet by United States Navy sailors.<ref name=gainesp132>Gaines, p. 132.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==23 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=23 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Courier''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] collided with the schooner ''Wirralite'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank off [[Donaghadee]], [[County Down]].<ref name=Times250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Emma'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Holm Sands, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Norfolk]]. She was on a voyage from [[Alexandria]], [[Egypt Eyalet|Egypt]] to [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Miner''\n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British North America]]\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the south coast of [[St. Paul Island (Nova Scotia)|St. Paul Island]], [[Nova Scotia]]. She was on a voyage from [[Yarmouth, Nova Scotia]] to [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]].<ref name=Times120963>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=12 September 1863 |page_number=6 |issue=24662 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Propitious'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] sprang a leak and was beached at [[Great Yarmouth]], [[Norfolk]]. She was on a voyage from the [[River Tyne]] to [[Maldon, Essex]]. She was refloated on 23 August and taken in to Great Yarmouth.<ref name=S250863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=25 August 1863 |issue=12180 |page=8 }}</ref><ref name=NC280863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==24 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=24 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Coiner'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] collied with the schooner ''Wirralite'' and sank off [[Drogheda]], [[County Louth]].<ref name=FJ250863>{{Cite news |title=Pier Head, Dublin |newspaper=Freeman's Journal |location=Dublin |date=25 August 1863 }}</ref> Her crew were rescued by ''Louise'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Coiner'' was on a voyage from [[Workington]], [[Cumberland]] to [[Belfast]], [[County Antrim]].<ref name=S270863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ranger''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] struck the Willow Rock and sank. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]] to [[Penzance]], [[Cornwall]].<ref name=Times250863>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=25 August 1863 |page_number=8 |issue=24646 |column=F }}</ref><ref name=S250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==25 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=25 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Coquette''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The [[schooner]], carrying a cargo of [[anchor]] and chain, was captured at the mouth of the [[Rappahannock River]] in [[Virginia]], [[Confederate States of America]], by the [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel paddle]] [[Tugboat|tug]] {{USS|Satellite|1854|6}} ({{navy|United States|1863}}), which was under the control of a [[Confederate States Navy]] crew that had captured her on 23 August. After stripping ''Coquette'', the Confederates burned her at [[Port Royal, Virginia|Port Royal]], [[Virginia]].<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Golden Rod''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: During a voyage from [[Baltimore, Maryland]], to [[Maine]] with a cargo of [[coal]], the [[schooner]], was captured at the mouth of the Rappahannock River and burned at [[Urbanna, Virginia]], by the [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel paddle]] [[Tugboat|tug]] {{USS|Satellite|1854|2}} ({{flag|Confederate States of America|1863}}), which was under the control of a [[Confederate States Navy]] crew that had captured her on 23 August.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863/><ref name=gainesp181>Gaines, p. 181.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS Savannah (gunboat)|CSS ''Oconee'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=The [[gunboat]] foundered in bad weather in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] during a voyage from [[Savannah, Georgia]], to [[England]] with a cargo of [[cotton]]. Her crew abandoned ship safely, but [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces captured 15 of them on 20 August. \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] sank off [[Formby]], [[Lancashire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Caernarfon]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=S310863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=31 August 1863 |issue=12185 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==26 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=26 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Fortitude'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brigantine]] ran aground and sank at [[Ballyshannon]], [[County Donegal]]. She was on a voyage from [[Whitehaven]], [[Cumberland]] to Ballyshannon.<ref name=S110963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=11 September 1863 |issue=12195 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Margaret and Ann''  <!--not Mary and Ann-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Castle Rock. She was on a voyage from [[Bangor, Caernarfonshire]] to [[Kyleakin]], [[Isle of Skye]], [[Outer Hebrides]].<ref name=S160963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=16 September 1863 |issue=12199 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==27 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=27 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''[[H. L. Hunley (submarine)|H. L. Hunley]]''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1863|name=Confederate States Army}}\n|desc=The [[submarine]] sank off [[Charleston, South Carolina]], during a test run in [[Charleston Harbor]] when she dived accidentally with her hatches open. The accident killed five members of her eight-man crew. She was refloated and returned to service. \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Iliade'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] capsized at [[Sunderland, County Durham]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was righted.<ref name=NC040963>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=4 September 1863 |issue=9845 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Norah'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}} \n|desc=The [[brigantine]] was wrecked off [[Casablanca]], Morocco. Her crew were rescued.<ref name=DN230963>{{Cite news |title=Telegraphic Intelligence |newspaper=Daily News |location=London |date=23 September 1863 |issue=5421 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sarah Jane'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was abandoned in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] off [[Casablanca]], Morocco. She was on a voyage from Casablanca to [[London]].<ref name=S150963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=15 September 1863 |issue=12198 |page=7 }}</ref><ref name=NC180963>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=18 September 1863 |issue=9847 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Seamew'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sprang a leak sank in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] ({{coord|37|16|N|15|40|W}}). Her thirteen crew were rescued by ''Albert'' ({{flag|France}}).<ref name=MP030963>{{Cite news |title=Fortunate Rescue at Sea |newspaper=Morning Post |location=London |date= September 1863 |issue=27991 |page=5 }}</ref><ref name=NC040963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==28 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=28 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''America''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: Carrying a cargo of [[cotton]] loaded at [[Corpus Christi, Texas]], [[Confederate States of America]], the [[schooner]] capsized in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] off the coast of Texas while under tow by the [[barque]] {{USS|William G. Anderson|1859|6}} ({{navy|United States|1863}}). ''William G. Anderson'' had captured her off Texas on 27 August.<ref name=gainesp165>Gaines, p. 165.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Neptune'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] ran aground and was wrecked on the Doggerbank, in the [[Irish Sea]] off the coast of [[County Wexford]].<ref name=S010963/> She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]] to [[Cardigan, Ceredigion|Cardigan]].<ref name=S080963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sunbeam''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=Carrying a cargo of [[whiskey]] and [[USD|US$]]10,000 in [[Coin|specie]], the [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel]] [[Passenger ship|passenger steamer]] sank during a storm in 132 feet (40 meters) of water in [[Lake Superior]] off [[Keweenaw Point]], 2 [[nautical mile]]s (3.7 km) east of [[Copper Harbor, Michigan|Copper Harbor]] or [[Eagle Harbor, Michigan]] ({{coord|47|29|00|N|87|47|48|W|name=''Sunbeam''}}).<ref>Gaines, p. 57.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==29 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=29 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ann'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore {{convert|3|nmi|km}} from [[Helmsdale]], [[Sutherland]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyge from [[Lybster]], [[Caithness]] to [[klaip\u0117da|Memel]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]]. She was refloated and taken in to Helmsdale.<ref name=DC040963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Caspar'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The ship foundered at sea. She was on a voyage from [[Pisagua, Chile]] to [[New York City|New York]].<ref name=BNL210963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Belfast News-Letter |location=Belfast |date=21 September 1863 |issue=32578 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Emma Gilmore'' <!--not Emma-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was lost off [[Cape Cod]], [[Massachusetts]], United States. She was on a voyage from [[Ardrossan]], [[Ayrshire]] to [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States.<ref name=CM150963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=15 September 1863 |issue=23149 }}</ref><ref name=S170963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=17 September 1863 |issue=12200 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lotus'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Bonar Bridge]], Sutherland.<ref name=DC040963>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=4 September 1863 |issue=3142 }}</ref> Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to Bonar Bridge.<ref name=LM070963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Neptune''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was wrecked on the Doggerbank, in the [[Irish Sea]] off the coast of [[County Wexford]].<ref name=Times010963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==30 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=30 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Auckland'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[New Zealand]]\n|desc=The [[cutter (boat)|cutter]] was wrecked near [[Godley Head]] in [[Lyttelton Harbour]]. All hands were saved but the ship sank quickly and all cargo and belongings were lost.<ref name=SNZD92/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Incentive'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] foundered off [[Looe Island]], [[Cornwall]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Gij\u00f3n]], Spain.<ref name=CM030963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Minerva''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was run down and sunk by the [[smack (ship)|smack]]  ''Elizabeth'' ({{flagcounry|UKGBI|civil}}) off [[Land's End]], [[Cornwall]]. One of her crew was rescued by the smack, the rest reached land in a boat. She was on a voyage from Cardiff to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]].<ref name=Times010963/><ref name=S010963/><ref name=CM030963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==31 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=31 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cestrian'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was abandoned off [[Newhaven, Sussex]]. Her four crew were rescued by the [[lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] ''Thomas Chapman'' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Royal National Lifeboat Institution]]). ''Cestrian'' was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]]. she subsequently came ashore east of Newhaven.<ref name=Renno>{{cite book |title=Beachy Head Shipwrecks of the 19th Century |first=David |last=Renno |pages=216-17 |publisher=Amhurst Publishing |location=Sevenoaks |year=2004 |isbn=1 903637 20 1}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Coquette''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The 50-ton [[schooner]] was destroyed by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] forces at [[Port Royal, Virginia|Port Royal]], [[Virginia]]. They had captured her at the mouth of the [[Rappahannock River]] on the night of 24\u201325 August.<ref>Gaines, p. 177.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Johanna and Bennich'' \n|flag=[[File:POL Szczecin flag.svg|22px]] [[Stettin]] \n|desc=The [[galiot]] ran aground on the Shipwash Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Borga]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]] to [[Bordeaux]], [[Gironde]], France. She was reflaoted and put in to [[Harwich]], [[Essex]], United Kingdom.<ref name=S080963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=8 September 1863 |issue=12192 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Seraphine'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[sloop]] struck the [[Longships, Cornwall|Longships Rocks]], [[Cornwall]]. She was assisted in to [[Plymouth]], [[Devon]] in a leaky condition.<ref name=S010963>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=1 September 1863 |issue=12186 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Windham'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] foundered in the [[English Channel]] off [[Berry Head]], Devon. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[Bridgwater]], [[Somerset]].<ref name=CM030963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=3 September 1863 |issue=23139 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==Unknown date==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=Unknown date in August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Delhi'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] sprang a leak at [[Madras]], [[British Raj|India]]. She was consequently condemned.<ref name=LM110863/><ref name=S110863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Earl of Auckland'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] sank off [[Brielle]], [[South Holland]], Netherlands.<ref name=LM120863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=12 August 1863 |issue=4838 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elena'', or<br>''Enea'' \n|flag=[[File:Austria-Hungary-flag-1869-1914-naval-1786-1869-merchant.svg|22px]] [[Austrian Empire]] \n|desc=The [[barque]] was lost off [[Cape St. Vincent]], Portugal before 4 August. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Trieste]].<ref name=LM110863/><ref name=S110863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Emma'' \n|flag=Flag unknown<!--described as \"foreign\"-->\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked {{convert|2|nmi|km}} north of [[Cape de Gatt]], Spain on or before 8 August. Her crew survived.<ref name=CM150863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Everglade'' \n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The [[steamship]] was sunk off [[Tybee Island, Georgia]] by a [[United States Navy]] squadron. Twenty-two passengers were taken [[prisoner of war|prisoner]]. She was on a voyage from [[Savannah, Georgia]] to [[Nassau, Bahamas]].<ref name=CM110963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=11 September 1863 |issue=23146 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Helena'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked at \"Sokken\". She was on a voyage from [[Grangemouth]], [[Stirlingshire]] to [[Cronstadt]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]].<ref name=LM130863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=13 August 1863 |issue=4839 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Idelia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Elwick, Northumberland]]. She was on  a voyage from [[Vyborg]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]] to [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]].<ref name=LM110863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=11 August 1863 |issue=4387 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lucy'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was wrecked in Duncan's Passage before 10 August. She was on a voyage from [[Calcutta]], India to [[Colombo]], [[Ceylon]].<ref name=CM160963>{{Cite news |title=Shippin Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=16 September 1863 |issue=23150 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Princess Alexandra''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was abandoned in the [[North Sea]]{{convert|90|nmi|km}} north east of [[Flamborough Head]], [[East Riding of Yorkshire|Yorkshire]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[G\u00e4vle]], Sweden to [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull, Yorkshire]].<ref name=Times250863/><ref name=S250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Reliance|1860|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Captured by a [[Confederate States Navy]] crew on 23 August, the armed [[screw steamer]] was destroyed by Confederate forces at [[Port Royal, Virginia]], either on 25 August or between 28 and 31 August to prevent her recapture by [[cavalry]] forces under [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Judson Kilpatrick]] ({{flag|United States|1863|name=United States Army}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863/><ref name=gainesp187>Gaines, p. 187.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Retreat''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the [[Irish Sea]] off the coast of [[Denbighshire]]. Her crew survived.<ref name=Times010963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Salacia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore in the Mud Islands, [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]]. She was refloated on 3 August and taken in to [[Pubnico (village), Nova Scotia|Pubnico]] in a [[hogging and sagging|hogged]] and waterlogged condition.<ref name=CM010963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=1 September 1863 |issue=23137 }}</ref><ref name=S010963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Satellite|1854|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Captured by a [[Confederate States Navy]] crew on 23 August, the armed [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel]] [[Tugboat|tug]] was destroyed by Confederate] forces at Port Royal, either on 25 August or between 28 and 31 August to prevent her recapture by [[cavalry]] forces under [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[Judson Kilpatrick]] ({{flag|United States|1863|name=United States Army}}).<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863/><ref name=\"gainesp187-188\">Gaines, pp. 187-188.</ref> The armed [[Steamship|steamer]]  {{USS|Commodore Read}}  ({{navy|United States|1863}}) detonated 50 pounds (22.7 kg) of [[gunpowder]] in her [[boiler]] on 31 May 1864 to prevent her [[Marine salvage|salvage]] by the Confederates.<ref name=gainesp187-188>Gaines, pp. 187-188.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sea Crest''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] ran aground off Long Point, British North America. She was on a voyage from [[St. Stephen, New Brunswick]], British North America to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]. She was refloated.<ref name=Times010963>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=1 September 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24652 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sharp''\n|flag={{flag|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=American Civil War: The [[Steamship|steamer]] was burned and sunk by the Confederates in the [[Sunflower River]] in [[Mississippi]] to prevent her capture by [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] forces.<ref>[https://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/confederate_ships/sharp.html Naval History and Heritage Command: Confederate Ships: Sharp]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''St. Pierre'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore near [[Pennington, Hampshire]], United Kingdom. She was on a voyage from [[Rotterdam]], South Holland to [[Nantes]], [[Loire-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=LM120863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sumter''\n|flag={{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 212-ton [[Steamship|steamer]], a [[Troopship|transport]] carrying the [[20th South Carolina Regiment]], the [[23rd South Carolina Regiment]], and [[Captain Matthew's Artillery Company]] (all {{army|Confederate States of America|1863}}), was shelled by Confederate [[artillery]] at [[Fort Wagner]] and [[Battery Gregg]] on [[Sullivan's Island, South Carolina]] that mistook her for a [[United States Navy]] [[Monitor (ship)|monitor]] in [[fog]] and heavy weather while she was entering [[Charleston Harbor]] at [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina]], without showing a recognition light on 30 or 31 August. She sank in two hours with the loss of 40 killed, one wounded, and eight missing. More than 600 survivors were rescued by [[barge]]s and [[Confederate States Navy]] [[gunboat]]s.<ref name=gainesp156>Gaines, p. 156.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Thistle'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[New Zealand]]\n|desc=The [[cutter (boat)|cutter]] was wrecked on the Kawhia Bar, at the mouth of [[Kawhia Harbour]]. All on board were lost.<ref name=SNZD92/> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Two Brothers''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Carrying a cargo of [[anchor]]s and anchor chains to [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], the 49-ton [[schooner]] was captured by a [[Confederate States Navy]] crew aboard the captured armed [[Tugboat|tug]] {{USS|Satellite|1854|6}} ({{flag|Confederate States of America|1863}}) at the mouth of the [[Rappahannock River]] in [[Virginia]] Confederate States of America on the night of 24\u201325 August, then was stripped and burned at [[Port Royal, Virginia]], on either 25 or 31 August.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863/><ref name=\"gainesp189\">Gaines, p. 189.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Westfield'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at Bootman's Head, British North America. She was on a voyage from \"Lepraux\" to Liverpool. She was refloated and towed in to [[West Quoddy, Nova Scotia]] in a waterlogged condition and placed under repair.<ref name=LM240863/><ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unidentifed schooner\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=American Civil War: Carrying a cargo of [[coal]], the [[schooner]] was sunk by Confederate guerrillas off [[Urbanna, Virginia]], [[Confederate States of America]].<ref name=\"gainesp192\">Gaines, p. 192.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* [http://scubagonewild.com/documents/Encyclopedia%20of%20Civil%20War%20Shipwrecks%20-%20(Malestrom).pdf Gaines, W. Craig, ''Encyclopedia of Civil War Shipwrecks'', Louisiana State University Press, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8071-3274-6}}.]\n* Ingram, C. W. N., and Wheatley, P. O., (1936) ''Shipwrecks: New Zealand disasters 1795\u20131936.'' Dunedin, NZ: Dunedin Book Publishing Association.\n\n{{shipevents|1863}}\n{{1860s shipwrecks}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of shipwrecks by year|1863-08]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1863| Shipwrecks08]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThe '''list of shipwrecks in August 1863''' includes ships sunk, foundered, grounded, or otherwise lost during August [[1863]].\n{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Calendar ToC}}\n\n==1 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=1 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Georgia|1863|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground off [[Nantucket]], [[Massachusetts]], United States. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=LM240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jeune Frederick'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[lugger]] sank {{convert|4|nmi|km}} north east of [[Abrevach]], [[Finist\u00e8re]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[Newport, Monmouthshire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Fontarabia]], Spain.<ref name=LM110863/><ref name=S110863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Storm Cloud'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashoyre at [[Akyab]], [[British Burma|Burma]] and broke in two. She was on a voyage from Akyab to a European port.<ref name=S180963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=Unnamed \n|flag=Flag unknown\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The ship was sunk off [[Charleston, South Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]] by {{USS|New Ironsides}} ({{navy|USA|1863}}) with the loss of all hands.<ref name=CM220863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=22 August 1863 |issue=23129 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==2 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=2 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Coriolanus''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship sprang a leak and was beached on [[Langlade Island]], where she became a wreck. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Miramichi, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]] to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]<ref name=Times010963/><ref name=GH020963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=2 September 1863 |issue=7378 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Idalia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore on [[F\u00e5r\u00f6]], Sweden. She was on a voyage from [[Vyborg]], [[Grand Duchy of Finland]] to [[West Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]]. She was refloated and taken in to \"Ekwik\" in a waterlogged condition.<ref name=S110863/><ref name=NC140863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Eglington''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground on the Aceitera Flats, off [[Cape Trafalgar]], Spain. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=Times100863>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Bombay and Mauritius Mails |date=10 August 1863 |page_number=7 |issue=24633 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==3 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date3= August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Halcyon'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] foundered off [[Great Cumbrae Island]], [[Argyllshire]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[Ardrossan]], [[Ayrshire]] to [[Newry]], [[County Antrim]].<ref name=DC080863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''St. Vincent'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Her crew were rescued by ''Hannah Secor'' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''St. Vincent'' was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], [[Virgin Islands]].<ref name=LM070863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=7 August 1863 |issue=4834 }}</ref><ref name=CM080863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=8 August 1863 |issue=23117 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==4 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=4 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Georgia|1863|2}}\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground and was wrecked at [[Cape Sable Island]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]]. All on board were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]].<ref name=Times290863>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Americe |date=29 August 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24650 |column=B-D }}</ref><ref name=Georgia>{{cite web |url=http://www.tynebuiltships.co.uk/G-Ships/georgia1863.html |title=Georgia |publisher=Shipping & Shipbuilding Research Trust |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==5 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=5 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gulterus'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] struck an [[iceberg]] in the Atlantic Ocean. She was set afire and abandoned by her crew, who were rescued by the [[schooner]] ''Prince'' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Jersey]]. ''Gulterus'' was on a voyage from [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to Liverpool.<ref name=LM040963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=4 September 1863 |issue=4858 }}</ref><ref name=CM050963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=5 September 1863 |issue=23141 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ruth''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 702-ton sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] was set afire by [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] agents on the [[Mississippi River]] at [[Lucas Bend]], {{convert|4|nmi|km}} below [[Norfolk, Missouri]]. She was engulfed in flames within five minutes and burned for five hours before sinking in {{convert|18|ft|m}} of water. Thirty lives were lost. Her wreck was blown up with [[gunpowder]] on 19 October.<ref name=gainesp102>Gaines, p. 102.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Union Packet'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] was driven ashore on [[Sheep Island, Pembrokeshire]] and was abandoned by her crew. She was refloated with assistance from the smack ''Amity'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and taken in to [[Milford Haven]], [[Pembrokeshire]], where she sank.<ref name=CM080863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==6 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=6 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anglo-Saxon'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. Her twelve crew were rescued by ''Reciprocity'' ({{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[British North America]]) ''Anglo-Saxon'' was on a voyage from [[Montreal]], [[Province of Canada]], British North America to [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]].<ref name=S220863/><ref name=NC280863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Barclay'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship struck a rock off [[Swinem\u00fcnde]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] and was damaged.<ref name=CM080863/> She was on a voyage from Swinem\u00fcnde to [[London]]. She consequently put in to [[Stettin]].<ref name=DC080863>{{Cite news |title=Dundee Shipping |newspaper=Dundee Courier |location=Dundee |date=8 August 1863 |issue=3119 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cheshire'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground and was wrecked at [[Musquash, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]]. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to [[Saint John, New Brunswick]].<ref name=LM240863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=24 August 1863 |issue=4848 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Paw Paw|1863|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The centerwheel [[paddle steamer]] sank within 15 minutes of striking a [[Snag (ecology)|snag]] in the [[Mississippi River]] near [[Hardin's Point]], [[Arkansas]]. She was refloated, repaired, and returned to service.\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Storm Cloud'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was lost near [[Akyab]], [[British Burma|Burma]].<ref name=LM070963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=7 September 1863 |issue=4860 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==7 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=7 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Rudolph'' \n|flag=[[File:Civil flag of Oldenburg.svg|22px]] [[Grand Duchy of Oldenburg]] \n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked at \"Dembeck\", near [[\u0141eba|Leba]], [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to [[Aberdeen]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]].<ref name=LM140863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=14 August 1863 |issue=4840 }}</ref><ref name=CM150863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercury |location=Edinburgh |date=15 August 1863 |issue=23123 }}</ref><ref name=AJ190863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=19 August 1863 |issue=6032 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==8 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=8 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Carleton'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] sprang a leak and was beached at [[Harwich]], [[Essex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Seaham]], [[County Durham]] to [[London]].<ref name=S110863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=11 August 1863 |issue=12168 |page=7 }}</ref><ref name=NC140863>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=London |date=14 August 1863 |issue=9842 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Faith''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=Carrying a cargo of [[coal]] intended for [[United States Navy]] ships [[Union blockade|blockading]] [[Charleston, South Carolina]], [[Confederate States of America]], the [[barque]] ran ashore and bilged off [[Port Royal, South Carolina]].<ref name=gainesp145>Gaines, p. 145.</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Norfolk Hero'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Hermes Spit in the [[Gulf of Smyrna]]. She was on a voyage from [[Swansea]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Smyrna]], [[Ottoman Empire]].<ref name=S190863a/> She was refloated the next day and taken in to Smyrna.<ref name=S250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Spanish frigate|Petronila|1855|2}}\n|flag={{navy|Spain|1785}}\n|desc=The {{sclass-|Petronila|frigate}} was wrecked at [[Mariel, Cuba]]. Her crew survived.<ref name=Times190963>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The India, China, and Australian Mails |date=19 September 1863 |page_number=6 |issue=24668 |column=F }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Pico'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked in the [[Gut of Canso]]. She was on a voyage from [[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States to [[Pictou]], [[Nova Scotia]], [[British North America]].<ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Secret'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was damaged by fire at [[Gothenburg]], Sweden.<ref name=S110863/> She was repaired and departed on 14 August for [[Bridgwater]], [[Somerset]].<ref name=S190863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==9 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=9 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Cambria''\n|flag={{flag|Bremen}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] struck an [[iceberg]] in the [[Atantic Ocean]]. She was abandoned on 12 August and set afire. Her crew were rescued by ''Lotus'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Cambria'' was on a voyage from [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to the [[River Clyde|Clyde]].<ref name=Times250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Commodore'' \n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The [[Steamship|steamer]] was lost south of [[Point Judith, Rhode Island|Point Judith]], [[Rhode Island]].<ref name=gainesp140>Gaines, p. 140.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Gloucestershire''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[full-rigged ship]] was partly abandoned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] in a waterlogged condition. Twelve of her seventeen crew were taken off by the [[schooner]] ''Electric Spark'' ({{flag|United States|1863}}). ''Gloucestershire'' was on a voyage from [[Saint John, New Brunswick]], [[British North America]] to [[London]].<ref name=Times010963/><ref name=LM010963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=1 September 1863 |issue=4855 }}</ref><ref name=S010963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Helen Inglis'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore and wrecked near \"Lakken\", Denmark. She was on a voyage from [[Grangemouth]], [[Stirlingshire]] to [[danzig|Dantsic]].<ref name=S170863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==10 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=10 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jeanette Melanie'' \n|flag={{flag|Belgium}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] foundered off [[Cabo da Roca]], Portugal. She was on a voyage from [[Lisbon]], Portugal to [[Ostend]], [[West Flanders]].<ref name=CM190863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Jeune Adele'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked on a reef south east of [[Bermuda]]. She was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]] to [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint Thomas]], [[Virgin Islands]].<ref name=S150963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hoppett'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was run ashore and wrecked at \"Ruberg\", Denmark. She was on a voyage from [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] to [[Cronstadt]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]].<ref name=LM130863/><ref name=NC140863/><ref name=S170863a/><ref name=NC210863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==11 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=11 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Beatitude'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship collided with another vessel in the [[Noordhollandsch Kanaal]]. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Amsterdam]], [[North Holland]], Netherlands. She was taken in to Amsterdam in a sinking condition. Subsequently placed under repair.<ref name=CM190863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Caledonian Mercrury |location=Edinburgh |date=19 August 1863 |issue=23126 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Sea Gull'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[New Zealand]]\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was struck by lightning off the coast of [[Taranaki]], destroying the mainmast and starting a fire. To save the lives of those on board, the skipper deliberately beached the ship near the mouth of the Henui River (Te Henui Stream, [[New Plymouth]]).<ref name=SNZD92>Ingram & Wheatley, p. 92.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==12 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=12 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{PS|Celt|1848|2}}, and<br>''Garibaldi'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] ''Garibaldi'' collided with the [[paddle steamer]] ''Celt'' and sank in the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] at [[Port Glasgow]], [[Renfrewshire]]. Her two crew were rescued. ''Celt'' ran aground. Her passengers were taken off by another steamshis.<ref name=AJ190863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==13 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=13 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lydia'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Calais]], France. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to Calais.<ref name=CM190863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Peccione'' \n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The ship was wrecked on the La Folle Reef. She was on a voyage from [[Jacmel]], Haiti to [[Havre de Gr\u00e2ce]], [[Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]].<ref name=LM110963>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=11 September 1863 |issue=4854 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Triumph'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven from her moorings and ran aground at [[Narva]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]]. She was refloated the next day.<ref name=S220863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==14 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=14 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Aid'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground and sank off [[Dagerort]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Sunderland, County Durham]] to [[Cronstadt]], [[Russian Empire|Russia]].<ref name=S170863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Eliza''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brigantine]] collided with another vessel and was abandoned off the [[Smalls Lighthouse]], [[Cornwall]]. Her crew were rescued by the [[schooner]] ''Moses Parry'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}). ''Eliza'' was on a voyage from [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]] to [[Galway]].<ref name=Times190863/><ref name=S190863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Tynemouth'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground at [[South Shields]], [[County Durham]]. She was on a voyage from [[Cartagena, Spain]] to South Shields. She was refloated.<ref name=S170863a>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=17 August 1863 |issue=12173 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==15 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=15 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Bee'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was holed by a [[groyne]] and sank at [[Eastbourne]], [[Sussex]]. She was on a voyage from [[Hartlepool]], [[County Durham]] to Eastbourne. Following temporary repairs, she was taken in to [[Newhaven, Sussex]] on 17 August.<ref name=NC210863>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=17 August 1863 |issue=9843 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Her Majesty'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] struck a rock off [[Bembridge]], [[Isle of Wight]]. Her passengers were taken off by [[pilot boat]]s before she sank. She was on a round the island voyage from [[Ryde]].<ref name=S170863>{{Cite news |title=Wreck of a Passenger Steamer off the Isle of Wight |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=17 August 1863 |issue=12173 |page=2 }}</ref> She was refloated on 18 August and towed in to [[Portsmouth]], [[Hampshire]] by the [[tugboat|tug]] ''Echo'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|government}}) and the steamship ''Prince Consort'' ({{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}).<ref name=S190863>{{Cite news |title=Naval and Military Intelligence |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=19 August 1863 |issue=12175 |page=3 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Lady Louisa'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore between the [[Hurst Spit]] and [[Lymington]], [[Hampshire]]. She was on a voyage from [[Waterford]] to [[Southampton]], Hampshire. She was refloated and completed her voyage.<ref name=S190863a/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==16 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=16 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Bellona'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British North America]]\n|desc=The [[schooner]] was driven ashore at [[Cutler, Maine]], United States and was abandoned by her crew. She was on a voyage from [[Saint John, New Brunswick]] to [[New York City|New York]], United States. She was refloated and taken in to Cutler.<ref name=S080963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Good Intent'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[galiot]] foundered off [[Cap-d'Antifer]], [[Seine-Inf\u00e9rieure]], France. Her five crew were rescued by the [[lugger]] ''Jeune Albert'' ({{flag|France}}). ''Good Intent'' was on a voyage from [[Pont-Audemer]], [[Eure]], France to [[Sunderland, County Durham]].<ref name=LM260863/><ref name=NC280863>{{Cite news |title=Marine Intelligence |newspaper=Newcastle Courant |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=28 August 1863 |issue=9844 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Joseph and Mary''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground off [[Flotta]], [[Orkney Islands]]. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Lerwick]], [[Shetland Islands]].<ref name=Times250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ruby''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[steamship]] ran aground and broke her back at [[Burnham-on-Sea]], [[Somerset]]. She was on a voyage from Burnham-on-Sea to [[Cardiff]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=Times190863>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Ship News |date=19 August 1863 |page_number=12 |issue=24641 |column=C }}</ref> She was later refloated and taken in to [[Bristol]], [[Gloucestershire]] for repairs.<ref name=Times250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William Bromham'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] ran aground and became waterlogged at [[Aberdovey]], [[Merionethshire]]. Her crew were rescue; some of them by the Aberdovey Lifeboat. She was on a voyage from [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]] to Aberdovey.<ref name=CM190863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==17 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=17 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Crocus|1862|6}}\n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: The armed [[screw steamer]] was wrecked on [[Bodie Island|Bodie\u2032s Island]], [[North Carolina]], [[British North America]].<ref name=gainesp117>Gaines, p. 117.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Urania'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[British North America]]\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the North Reef, off [[Antigua]]. She was on a voyage from [[New York City|New York]], United States to Antigua. She was refloated.<ref name=CM160963/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==18 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=18 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Elizabeth'' \n|flag={{flag|Norway|1844}}\n|desc=The ship ran aground on the Cross Sand, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Norfolk]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]. She was on a voyage from [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[Northumberland]], United Kingdom to [[C\u00e1diz]], Spain. She was refloated and taken in to [[Great Yarmouth]], Norfolk in a leaky condition.<ref name=S190863a>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=19 August 1863 |issue=12175 |page=8 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Hebe''\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]], [[Union blockade]]: Pursued by the armed [[screw steamer]] {{USS|Niphon|1863|6}} and the armed sidewheel [[paddle steamer]] {{USS|Shokokon|1862|6}} (both {{navy|United States|1863}}), the screw steamer, carrying a cargo of [[coffee]], clothing, [[medicine]], and provisions, ran aground on [[Pleasure Island (North Carolina)|Federal Point]], north of [[Fort Fisher]], [[North Carolina]] and was abandoned by her crew. According to one source, the ''Shokokon'' then riddled her with gunfire, igniting a fire that burned her to the [[waterline]]. According to another source, six United States Navy warships shelled ''Hebe''\u2032s wreck on 20 August, destroying her machinery and completing her destruction.<ref name=usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863>[http://www.usnlp.org/navychronology/1863b.html usnlp.org Navy Chronology of the Civil War, July-December 1863]</ref><ref name=gainesp121>Gaines, p. 121.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Mary Campbell'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] struck a sunken rock and foundered in the Sount of Callaway with the loss of two of her crew.<ref name=GH240863>{{Cite news |title=Greenock |newspaper=Glasgow Herald |location=Glasgow |date=24 August 1863 |issue=7370 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS Savannah (gunboat)|CSS ''Oconee'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=The [[gunboat]] foundered in bad weather in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] south of [[St. Catherines Island]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], during a voyage from [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], to [[England]] with a cargo of [[cotton]]. Her crew abandoned ship safely, but a [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] ship captured 15 of them off the coast of [[Florida]] on 20 August.<ref name=gainesp43>Gaines, p. 43.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ranger'' <!--not Hero-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Kilkee]], [[County Clare]]. Her crew were rescued. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Quebec City]], [[Province of Canada]], [[British North America]].<ref name=LM210863/><ref name=CM220863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==19 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=19 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Clara Ellen'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at Soldier's Point. She was on a voyage from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]] to [[Miramichi]], [[New Brunswick]], [[British North America]]. She was refloated on 27 August and taken in to [[Dundalk]], [[County Louth]] in a severely leaky condition.<ref name=S310863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ellen and Sarah'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[Mersey Flat]] collided with the [[pilot boat]] ''No. 9'' ({{Flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}) and sank at [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]]. She was refloated.<ref name=LM210863>{{Cite news |title=Shipping Intelligence |newspaper=Liverpool Mercury |location=Liverpool |date=21 August 1863 |issue=4846 }}</ref><ref name=S220863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=22 August 1863 |issue=12178 |page=7 }}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Helen Jane'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was wrecked at [[Aveiro, Portugal]] with the loss of one of her seven crew and one reported missing.<ref name=S220863/> She was on a voyage from [[Oporto]], Portugal to [[London]].<ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=[[CSS Robert Habersham|CSS ''Robert Habersham'']]\n|flag={{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}\n|desc=The 173- or 200-ton [[Paddle steamer|sidewheel]] [[Troop transport|transport]] suffered a [[boiler]] explosion on the [[Savannah River]] at [[Savannah, Georgia]], that wrecked her, injured at least eight to ten people, and may have killed her entire crew of 25.<ref name=gainesp50>Gaines, p. 50.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=x-XcAgWYTMMC&pg=PA180&lpg=PA180&dq=%22Robert+Habersham%22+explosion+August+1863&source=bl&ots=wTjDnPO3AF&sig=ix4uvnqsugAvtBwnAHKiNFW4hN4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvlbKFw4fWAhVBRWMKHcTkByMQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=Habersham&f=false Silverstone, Paul H., ''Civil War Navies, 1855-1883'', New York: Routledge/Taylor & Francis, 2006, {{ISBN|0-415-97870-X}}, p. 180.]</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Scout'' \n|flag={{flagicon|UKGBI|civil}} [[Jersey]]\n|desc=The [[smack (ship)|smack]] ran aground at [[Gardenstown]], [[Aberdeenshire]].  She was refloated.<ref name=CM270863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==20 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=20 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Adelicia'' <!--not Salacia-->\n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[barque]] was driven ashore and wrecked at [[Horsey, Norfolk]]. Her crew survived. She was on a voyage from [[London]] to [[Sunderland, County Durham]].<ref name=LM210863/><ref name=S220863/><ref name=S240863>{{Cite news |title=Mercantile Ship News |newspaper=The Standard |location=London |date=24 August 1863 |issue=12179 |page=8 }}</ref><ref name=NC280863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Bessy Bent'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The ship was driven ashore at [[Breaksea Point]], [[Glamorgan]].<ref name=LM240863/><ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Petit Corporal''\n|flag={{flag|France}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] was driven ashore on [[Anholt (Denmark)|Anholt]], Denmark.<ref name=Times250863/><ref name=LM250863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''William S. Bull''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The 16-ton [[screw steamer]] foundered in [[Lake Erie]] about 40 [[nautical mile]]s (74 km) from [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=gainesp56>Gaines, p. 56.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==21 August==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=21 August 1863 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anglo Saxon''\n|flag={{flag|United States|1863}}\n|desc=[[American Civil War]]: The 868-ton [[clipper]], bound from [[Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]], to [[New York City|New York]] with a cargo of [[coal]], was captured and burned in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] near [[Brest, France|Brest]], [[Finist\u00e8re]], France by the [[Screw steamer|screw]] [[sloop-of-war]] [[CSS Florida (cruiser)|CSS ''Florida'']] ({{navy|Confederate States of America|1863}}).<ref name=macslogflorida>[http://ahoy.tk-jk.net/MaraudersCivilWar/CSSFlorida.html Ahoy - Mac's Web Log \"Marauders of the Sea, Confederate Merchant Raiders During the American Civil War: CSS Florida. 1862-1863. Captain John Newland Maffitt. CSS Florida. 1864. Captain Charles M. Morris\"]</ref><ref name=\"usnlpcivilwarchronologyJulDec1863\" /><ref name=gainesp36>Gaines, p. 36.</ref> \n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Anna Maria'' \n|flag={{flagcountry|UKGBI|civil}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] ran aground on the Newcombe Sands, in the [[North Sea]] off the coast of [[Suffolk]]. She was refloated and resumed her voyage.<ref name=S240863/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{USS|Bainbridge|1842|6}} \n|flag={{navy|United States|1863}}\n|desc=The [[brig]] capsized and sank in the [[North Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Cape Hatteras]], [[North Carolina]]. Only two members of her crew survived the sinking to escape in a boat, but one of them became crazed, jumped overboard, and drowned. ''South Boston'' (flag unknown) rescued the only surviving crewman two days later.<ref name=gainesp114>Gaines, p. 114.</ref> \n}}\n{{